<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Conference Urges End to Kosovo Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Conference on
Tuesday condemned the persistent violence in the Serbian province
of Kosovo, calling for an immediate end to it.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the European Union (EU) member states,
all the 11 applicant countries for EU membership and Switzerland
stressed the importance of the adoption of United Nations Security
Council Resolution 1199.
</P>
<P>
They also urged Belgrade to comply fully and immediately with
the resolution, which calls for an immediate ceasefire, adopted on
September 23.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel of Austria, which holds the
rotating EU presidency, said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
report on Kosovo Monday showed that the excessive use of force
against civilians was continuing.
</P>
<P>
Another 20,000 people were made homeless in the Yugoslav
province after the adoption of the U.N. resolution, Schuessel
quoted the U.N. report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Those at the conference also urged Belgrade to immediately
investigate, and identify and punish those responsible for the
alleged atrocities against civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the Belgrade authorities to allow and support actively
an immediate return of all refugees and displaced persons to their
homes," said a statement issued by the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference participants reiterated their call both to the
authorities in Belgrade and the leaders of the ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo to resolve the situation through dialogue with
international mediation.
</P>
<P>
The inaugural European Conference was held in March this year
at the level of heads of state and government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
