<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEM Conference on Child Welfare Opens in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The ASEM (Asia-Europe Meeting)
conference on child welfare opened in London early Tuesday and a
British minister called for closer international cooperation on
children protection.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the three-day conference,
British Foreign Office minister Derek Fatchett said: "We need to
work more closely together to combat child sex tourism. We need to
strengthen our exchange of information and intelligence"
</P>
<P>
"We need to understand better our differing systems of justice;
We need to work more closely to pursue and prosecute the
offender," he added.
</P>
<P>
Information release by children's charities revealed that in
Asia alone, more than 650,000 children under the age of 16 work as
prostitutes and that one million children enter the global sex
market every year.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett made it clear: "We have a duty to ensure the innocence
of children is not corrupted by the evil lust for child
prostitution. That's why your work today is so important."
</P>
<P>
Representative from 15 European Union (EU) countries and 10
Asian countries including China are expected to hold wide-ranging
discussions on better ways to protect vulnerable children.
</P>
</TEXT>
