<HEADLINE> Ivanisevic, Chang Through in Shanghai Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Top seeds Goran Ivanisevic of
Croatia and Michael Chang of the United States advanced into the
second round after tough-winning matches over their opponents at
the Shanghai Open tennis on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The big-hit Ivanisevic, world number 12, fired nine aces to
defeat Brett Steven of New Zealand 6-4, 7-6 (8-6) in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
"I feel tired because I didn't sleep well last night," the
top-seeded Croatian said of his hard work in the second set. "But
I believe I can improve a lot tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
Suffering a rapid slip on the world ranking table, Chang,
second-seeded here and world No. 33, also met a strong challenge
after an easy first set, ousting Canadian Sebastien Larfau 6-2,
7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
Chang had no trouble to take the first set and built a 2-0
lead in the second before he connected to a series of unforced
errors.
</P>
<P>
Larfau dominated the net with speed and almost turned the
table around after he made it 6-5. However, the experienced Chang
recovered from his slum and regained the control of the game.
</P>
<P>
In day's other matches, seventh seed Kenneth Carlsen of
Denmark downed Martin Sinner of Germany 6-4, 6-3, while fourth
seed Mikael Tillstrom of Sweden was the only seed to be
eliminated from the tournament when he lost to Sargis Sargsian of
Armenia 6-3, 6-3.  
</P>
</TEXT>
