<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armstrong Battling Back From Cancer for World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Two years after being
diagnosed with testicular cancer that spread to his lungs and
brain, U.S. cyclist Lance Armstrong could complete one of the
greatest comebacks in sports history.
</P>
<P>
He is going to compete in the World Cycling Championships this
week and likely to win.
</P>
<P>
Armstrong, a two-time Olympian, won the road race world title
in 1993. Three years later, he learned of the cancer. The
European team he had been racing for dropped him.
</P>
<P>
Armstrong missed the entire 1997 season and began 1998 slowly.
In March, even Armstrong thought his career was over.
</P>
<P>
"When I left in the spring of 1998, there was a large part of
me that thought I would never come back," he said. "The day I
quit at Paris-Nice, I thought that was the last bike race I would
ever do.
</P>
<P>
"When I came home, I didn't unpack my bike for four weeks,"
said the 27-year-old Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
Gradually, Armstrong found he could not stay off his bike and
continued racing for the team sponsored by the U.S. Postal
Service.
</P>
<P>
He entered the Tour of Spain two weeks ago in preparation for
the World Championships, which begin Tuesday in Valkenburg,
Netherlands. His progression continued in Spain with his
fourth-place finish - eight seconds from third place.
</P>
<P>
The one-day test of cycling's greatest riders takes place
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"It is very much of a classic course, " said Armstrong, who
wants to compete in the 2000 Olympics in mountain bike racing.
"Very difficult, long and short steep climbs. I've heard it
described as a puncher's course. That suits me very well."
</P>
<P>
Armstrong said he races now not just to win but to show those
with cancer that there is hope. "I would like to be an example
for them, for all cancer patients, not just young men.
</P>
<P>
"I promised myself that I would do whatever I could in the
future to make it easier for the next person." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
