<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Union's Hunter: NBA's Decision No Surprise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The NBA's decision Monday to
cancel the preseason scheduled didn't surprise players union
executive director Billy Hunter.
</P>
<P>
Hunter said that the move is part of an attempt by the league
to intimidate players.
</P>
<P>
"It's unfortunate," Hunter said. "But I believe the league,
the owners and the commissioner decided they were going to play
hardball. They locked us out. They submitted a proposal with
mechanics they knew we wouldn't accept. They had no choice except
to cancel the preseason. We're not going to accept a bad deal,
and we're not going to be intimidated into accepting a bad deal."
</P>
<P>
To underscore their resolve, players will make themselves
available to fans and the media at several NBA arenas, training
sites and workout facilities today, which would have been the
first day of training camp.
</P>
<P>
Hunter said the idea came from the union's negotiating
committee and was first suggested by Washington Wizards forward
Juwan Howard, a member of the executive board.
</P>
<P>
"We've been trying to work out a settlement with the owners
and carve out a deal that's fair to both sides," Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
"We'll try to demonstrate to fans that's what we're trying to
do. Players will be around to enlighten fans as to what's
transpiring."
</P>
<P>
Hunter said the union hasn't planned any other activities at
this time, but it is considering staging a series of exhibition
games involving free agents if the lockout continues much longer.
</P>
<P>
He said a decision will be made about mid-October. Proceeds
from the games would go to charity and the players association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
