<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Accuses Cameroon of Oil Prospecting in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has accused Cameroon of
intending to prospect for oil in the disputed Bakassi Peninsula,
which was claimed by both countries.
</P>
<P>
"We want to bring to the notice of the international community
to the deliberate act of the Cameroonian Authority to wilfully
disregard the judgement of the International Court of Justice and
provoke hostilities in the Bakassi Peninsula," the Defense
Headquarters said in a statement in Lagos Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed by defense spokesman Lieutenant Colonel
S.A. Tella, quoted a report in a Cameroonian newspaper "Herald"
as saying that the Cameroonian government has signed a contract
with a Canadian company called Trophy Petroleum Company to
prospect for crude oil in Rio Del Ray for four years.
</P>
<P>
The company, with an initial capital of 13 million U.S.
Dollars, is to explore for oil in an area of over 2,300 square
kilometers around Rio Del Ray, which "is totally within the
disputed area of Bakassi between Nigeria and Cameroon," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"With this action, it is very clear that Cameroon intends to
stir up tension within the area. This is a new project contrary
to the injunction of the World Court to the two countries not to
embark on new projects within the disputed area," the Defense
Headquarters said.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the Nigerian ministries of Foreign
Affairs and Justice have been informed of the development and
asked to "take up the matter appropriately."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroon have clashed several times over the
oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula in the Guinea Gulf since 1993. The
dispute has been filed to the International Court of Justice but
no judgement has been made yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
