<HEADLINE> Jordan Testifies In Breach of Contract Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan was back in
court Monday in a breach-of-contract lawsuit, and the NBA
superstar denied he failed to go through with making a movie.
</P>
<P>
Jordan still denied he failed to make the movie Heaven is a
Playground because of the relatively small amount of money he
would have received.
</P>
<P>
Jordan had agreed to appear for $350,000 and later signed a $4
million deal to make Space Jam. Lawyer Robert Maland,
representing the producers of Heaven is a Playground, asked Jo
rdan if that didn't give his agent sufficient incentive to steer
him away from the movie.
</P>
<P>
"No," Jordan said. Jordan and agent David Falk contend the
producers failed to come up with adequate financing for the movie.
</P>
<P>
The producers are seeking for between $16 million and $20
million in damages, or what they believe could have been the
film's profit.
</P>
<P>
Jordan maintains both sides agreed to postpone the film, and
he has countersued, alleging the producers knowingly misled him
about financing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
