<HEADLINE> King's Company Loses Court Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. boxing promoter Don
King's company lost a Supreme Court appeal Monday in an insurance
fraud case that prosecutors have decided not to pursue.
</P>
<P>
Don King Productions had asked the high court to hear its
argument that King's testimony in a 1995 insurance fraud trial
should not be used against the company.
</P>
<P>
The high court turned down the company's appeal without
comment. The 1995 trial ended in a hung jury. In the second
trial that ended last July, King was acquitted of all charges
while the jury was unable to reach a verdict on charges against
his company.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said they will not seek a retrial of the company.
King was accused of altering a contract with a fighter to cheat
Lloyd's of London out of $350,000.
</P>
<P>
He had taken out an insurance policy with Lloyd's in case a
1991 fight between Julio Cesar Chavez and Harold Brazier was
canceled.
</P>
<P>
The fight was called off when Chavez got hurt training.
Prosecutors said King altered his contract with Chavez in a way
that would force Lloyd's to reimburse King but not against his
company, and he testified that the contract was altered without
his knowledge or approval.
</P>
<P>
The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled the testimony
could be used against King's company in the subsequent trial.
</P>
<P>
In appealing to the Supreme Court, lawyers for Don King
Productions said allowing use of King's testimony would violate
the company's right to confront the witnesses against it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earnings Rise in UK to Dampen Rate Cut Hopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A surprise upward revision to
average earnings growth figures in Britain has caught the
financial markets on the hop on Tuesday and cast fresh doubt on
the likelihood of an interest rate cut this week.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics released manufacturing and
industrial output figures, which were weaker than forecast. But
out of the blue it also revised up its estimates for annual
average earnings growth, to 5.0 percent from 4.7 in June and to
5.2 percent from 5.0 in May.
</P>
<P>
The pound, which has dropped sharply in recent days as the
markets bet the Bank of England would cut interest rates on
Thursday after a meeting of its Monetary Policy Committee,
rebounded to 2.7540 marks.
</P>
<P>
Jeremy Hawkins, economist at BankAmerica, was quoted by BBC as
saying: "This will not sit well with the Bank of England and must
reduce the likelihood of a rate move on Thursday."
</P>
<P>
"At the very least, it will make it extremely hard to justify
an ease of more than 25 basis points," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, an unexpectedly large cut in Spanish
interest rates on Tuesday, down half a percent to 3.75 percent,
was thought to increase the pressure for a U.K. rate cut.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output fell sharper than expected, 0.5 percent in
August, confirming the sector is teetering on the edge of
recession.
</P>
<P>
But wage growth has long been a bugbear for the central bank,
as it thinks earnings rising faster than 4.5 percent a year are
inconsistent with the government's 2.5 percent inflation target.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, most analysts are still betting the Bank will cut
its rate on Thursday, according to the BBC report. "There is a
growing feeling that the global financial turmoil may take
precedence over domestic matters," BBC said.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, Bank Governor Eddie George raised hopes of an
easing of monetary policy, saying: "There is clearly serious
weakness in some important parts of the world economy and the
balance of risks has shifted."
</P>
<P>
Pressure has been heaped on the Bank to act to help ease global
economic turmoil after the U.S. Federal Reserve cut its key rate
last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
