<HEADLINE> U.S. to Assist Angola in Refugee Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A visiting U.S. official James
Anderson announced here Tuesday that his country will provide 4.7
million U.S. Dollars for Angola's refugee settlement.
</P>
<P>
Anderson, head of United States Agency for International
Development (USAID), had met with Albino Malungo, Minister of
Assistance and Social Reintegration, and signed an aid agreement
which stipulated that USAID will donate 1.5 million Dollars to
help reintegrate former soldiers of the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), restore agricultural
production and develop rural education.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the United States will also assist Angolan
government and U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) 3.2
million Dollars to support the programs on repatriation of
Angolan refugees from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Describing the aid as "very precious", the minister said the
current situation of Angolan refugees is the worst since 1992.
</P>
<P>
At present, the southern African country has 790,000 refugees,
90 percent of them living a very hard life.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has donated 80 million Dollars to Angola
this year, of which 13 million is for helping clear landmines,
the rest is for purchasing food, medicine and materials for
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: UN Peacekeeping Mission Must Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony commemorating the 50th anniversary
of United Nations peacekeeping operations, Annan said, "
Peacekeeping, from the start, has been an improvisation. It
proved, and continues to prove, that the U.N. is not a static or
hidebound Organization, but a dynamic and innovative one."
</P>
<P>
"Peacekeeping has been one of many activities through which the
Organization has shown its ability to adapt to circumstances, to
find its way round obstacles, and to make itself relevant to the
actual problems at hand," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the evolution of U.N. peacekeeping from patrolling
clearly marked buffer zones and cease-fire lines to the far more
complex, multidimensional operations of the 1990s had been
either smooth or simple."
</P>
<P>
"Over the decades, We have had some unmistakable successes,
such as Namibia, Mozambique and El Salvador. We have also found
ourselves maintaining calm in some seemingly intractable
stalemates, such as Cyprus and the Middle East," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"And in some places -- Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia -- we
have found ourselves standing by while the most appalling crimes
were committed. There the limits of peacekeeping were
graphically demonstrated, " Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not here to declare the victory. We cannot claim that
peacekeeping has been the answer to every conflict. What we can
and do claim proudly is that, in the first half-century of their
existence, United Nations peacekeeping has saved tens of
thousands of lives, and it is one of the Organization's most
important and lasting contribution to the international peace
and security," Annan added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Says UK to Become Major Plutonium Storehouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Oxford Research Group said in
a study report Tuesday that Britain is set to become one of the
world's major storehouse for plutonium, the radiologically toxic
material.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the British stockpile of civil plutonium
is likely to double by the year 2010, at which time approximately
half of all the separated plutonium in the world will be in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The risks of storing such vast quantities of plutonium are
manifold. A primitive nuclear bomb could be fabricated relatively
easily while the ecological consequences of any accident could be
catastrophic, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Oxford Research Group also argues that the management of
this material is an environmental and a global security issue and
it wants more active government policy and greater public
accountability.
</P>
<P>
Brtain's large stocks arise because Britain is a leading
nuclear fuel reprocessor through state-owned British Nuclear Fuels
(BNFL), which receives spent nuclear fuel from reactors around the
world for reprocessing and storage.
</P>
<P>
The reprocessed fuel is eventually returned to the country it
originated from, but only after several years of storage in
Britain, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0017 </DOCNO>
