<HEADLINE> Kenyan and Ugandan Presidents Appeal for Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni and his Kenyan counterpart Daniel arap Moi have called
for peace in the region so that economy can be further developed.
</P>
<P>
They made the appeal at the opening ceremony of an
international trade fair here Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
On the conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC),
Museveni said that he hopes that hostility will be brought to an
end in the DRC so that it can start economic development.
</P>
<P>
President Moi, who came for a one-day visit, said he agreed
with what "his brother" had said and assured the public that his
country does not think terrorism can solve all the human problems
and therefore opposes all forms of terrorism totally.
</P>
<P>
The insecurity in DRC and southern Sudan poses a severe threat
to Uganda's safety, he said, adding that if there is no peace in
the region, this trade fair will not promote trade because people
dare not come out and buy things.
</P>
<P>
"I feel strongly that we should collect all the guns in Africa
so that people can move freely and fearlessly," the 74-year-old
president said.
</P>
<P>
Moi believed that only mediation and dialog can produce a
lasting solution to the security problems some of African
countries face now.
</P>
<P>
Both presidents once again condemned the disastrous bombings
in Nairobi and Dar-es-Salaam which occurred on August 7 and
expressed condolences to those who lost their dear ones in the
two incidents.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's border with Sudan was recently brought into the
limelight with a national mobilization in Sudan. The Khartoum
government closed all universities and colleges in the country
and asked all young people, who are capable of carrying guns, to
report to the nearest army barracks.
</P>
<P>
Sudan accused Uganda of sending troops to fight alongside with
the Sudan People's Liberation Army which has been fighting
against the Sudanese government for some 15 years. 
</P>
