<HEADLINE> Turkish President Accuses Syria of Supporting PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel Tuesday accused Syria of supporting the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) during his talks with visiting Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the presidential press center said that
Demirel explained the attitude of Syria which supports PKK to
Mubarak during their talks.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak arrived here Tuesday to find ways to defuse the
escalating crisis between Ankara and Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Demirel told Mubarak that Syria must stop supporting the PKK,
and the necessary concrete steps must be taken in the settlement
to the PKK issue, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of sheltering the PKK rebels,
who have been fighting since 1984 for autonomy for the Kurdish
minority in southeastern Turkey and frequently wage cross-border
raids on the Turkish military and civilian targets from their
camps in Iraq, Syria and Iran.
</P>
<P>
But Syria, together with Iran, has denied the charges, and
criticized, in return, Turkey for forming military alliance with
Israel that threatens the Arab security and undermines Syria's
bargaining position in the peace talks with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the presidents of Turkey and Egypt
had "cordial, open and detailed talks" on the mounting tensions
between Anakra and Damascus.
</P>
<P>
"We have talked to the Syrians. We have talked to the Turks,"
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters before
leaving Ankara for Syria.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Ambassador to Turkey Mehdi Fethullah told reporters
here that Mubarak left here for Syria to continue his mediation
between Ankara and Damascus after a five-hour short visit to
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak held talks with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad on
Sunday. 
</P>
