<HEADLINE> Schaeuble Set to Lead German Conservatives in Post-Kohl Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of outgoing chancellor
Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU) Tuesday decided to
nominate Wolfgang Schaeuble as new party chairman to succeed Kohl
who has decided to quit the post after an election defeat last
month.
</P>
<P>
Schaeuble, the 55-year-old preferred heir of Kohl, won the
nomination at a CDU leadership meeting in Bonn Tuesday. His
nomination has still to be approved by a party congress on
November 7.
</P>
<P>
At a separate meeting of parliamentary members of the CDU and
its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union (CSU),
Schaeuble was also confirmed as the leader of the joint
parliamentary group of the conservative alliance, a post he has
held since 1991.
</P>
<P>
With the possible twin leaderships, Schaeuble, who is Germany's
most popular politician according to opinion polls, is charged
with the task to rejuvenate the conservative camp which is
struggling to digest their worst defeat since 1949 in Germany's
general elections on September 27.
</P>
<P>
The election returned the Social Democratic Party to power
after 16 years in opposition.
</P>
<P>
Kohl has announced that he will give up the CDU chairmanship he
</P>
<P>
has held since 1973 to take personal responsibility for the
election defeat.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's decision immediately triggered a power struggle within
his party, with the younger leaders of the CDU calling for a
generational change to the party's leadership.
</P>
<P>
Volker Ruehe, the outgoing defense minister who comes third in
the party hierarchy, also openly criticized Kohl for declaring
Schaeuble the next party chairman before party leaders made the
decision on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to CDU officials, Ruehe is now one of the five
candidates for the party's four vise-chairman posts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
