<HEADLINE> 100623fff S. African International Trade Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- South African
International Trade Exhibition (SAITEX), the largest fair of the
kind in Africa, opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The five-day trade event attracted some 1,000 companies from
more than 40 countries around the world.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, South African Trade and Industry
Minister Alec Erwin called for the correction of unfair trade
relations between developed and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"If we do not correct the imbalance between developed and
developing, we will not solve the financial problems of the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
"It is no good having large funds in the developed world
seeking investment opportunities, if those investment
opportunities are not taking place in the South as we
industrialize our countries, become manufacturing economies and
trading economies in the world economy."
</P>
<P>
He said hopes for world economic growth lied in the South.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that the future growth in the world, despite
the current problems in emerging markets, despite the Southeast
Asian crisis,... does lie in the dramatic increase in trade and
investment between the southern hemisphere countries."
</P>
<P>
"SAITEX is one further step in building this relationship."
</P>
<P>
Erwin also criticized the European Union (EU) for its position
in free trade talks with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Talks broke down last month when the EU refused to make
concessions unless South Africa gives in on wine and spirit.
Erwin said the demand was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
But he said he was confident that the negotiations would
proceed.
</P>
<P>
Erwin also promised that South Africa would give market access
to its neighbors more rapidly and to a greater extent than they
would.
</P>
<P>
China stole the show on this year's SAITEX with its strong
presence. More than 200 companies are showcasing their products,
ranging from textiles to household appliances and machinery.
</P>
