<HEADLINE> OAU Calls for Negotiated Solution to Comorian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Ocean countries
and the Organization of African Unity (OAU) Tuesday called for a
peaceful and negotiated solution to the crisis in Comoros.
</P>
<P>
An OAU press release issued here said the member countries of
the Indian Ocean region and the OAU met Tuesday at the OAU
headquarters here at the ambassadorial level to consider the
development of the situation in the Comoros and exchange views on
the ways and means for a speedy settlement of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The release said W.A.W. Nhlapo, South African Permanent
Representativeto the OAU, briefed the meeting on the outcome of
the consultations on August 20 in Pretoria between the OAU and
the representatives of the separatists of Anjouan and another
ministerial meeting in Durban, South Africa, on September 1.
</P>
<P>
He also referred to the other on-going efforts aimed at
seeking an early solution to the crisis including the proposed
meeting between Comorian President Mohammed Taki Abdoulkarim and
Leader of the separatists of Anjouan Cheikh Abdallah Ibrahim,
under the auspices of President nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The participants expressed their serious concern about the
lack of progress in the search for a solution to the crisis as a
result of the intransigent and unrealistic position of the
Anjouanese separatists as demonstrated at the consultative
meeting held in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors believed that any initiative aimed at
consolidating the secessionist program, such as the organization
of the so-called legislative elections due to take place on
October 15 this year, would indicate lack of good faith and
cooperation and would jeopardize the on-going efforts.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors reiterated the determination of the OAU to
ensure the respect of the unity and territorial integrity of the
Comoros, said the release.
</P>
<P>
The participants strongly appealed to the Anjouanese
separatists to seize the opportunity of the proposed meeting
between President Taki and Cheikh Abdallah Ibrahim to commit
themselves to a peaceful and negotiated solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
