<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects Some War Compensation Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 5 (Xinhua)-- Iraq has accused that many
war compensation claims filed to the U.N. Compensation Committee
are coercive and unreasonable, the Iraqi News Agency reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadhan made the accusation
in two letters to U.N. secretary-general and the Security Council
president delivered by Iraq's permanent representative to the
U.N..
</P>
<P>
Ramadhan referred to an example in the letters to the
effect that a tourist company in Netherlands demands compensations
on the grounds that it had to cancel some tourist trips from
the Gulf region to Europe during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The vice president pointed out that compensation claims alike
had political purposes which aim to cause harm to the Iraqi
people and delay their right to development.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. statistics released earlier this month, so
far the U.N. Sanctions Committee has paid, from Iraq's proceeds
from oil sales, 1.9 billion U.S. dollars for war compensations.
</P>
<P>
Under U.N. resolutions, Iraq is allowed to export limited
amount of oil to buy food and medicine for its people. Around one
third of its proceeds from oil sales are earmarked for war
compensations.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since it invaded Kuwait in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
