<HEADLINE> Nigeria Strives to Be Self-Reliant in Weapon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, a major power in the
west Africa sub-region, is seeking to strengthen military
self-reliance by producing more weapons and logistics materials
itself.
</P>
<P>
A newsletter published recently by the Defense Headquarters
disclosed that Nigeria plans to develop its own hovercraft,
missile launcher and produce some aircraft equipment as well as
uniform fabrics and footwear.
</P>
<P>
According to the newsletter, the defense research and
development will collaborate with the Lagos State University to
develop an experimental prototype hovercraft capable of carrying
five passengers.
</P>
<P>
The said university has already developed a functional model
of the hovercraft, while all parts required for the production of
a prototype can be sourced locally, the newsletter said.
</P>
<P>
"The present hostilities in the Bakassi Peninsula (claimed by
both Nigeria and Cameroun) coupled with its marshy terrain favor
the use of the hovercraft by the Nigerian Armed Forces", the
newsletter said, adding it is appropriate that Nigeria
intensifies efforts to actualize the local production of
hovercraft.
</P>
<P>
A missile launcher project is also being proposed by the
defense research department. The newsletter said all inputs into
this project would be sourced locally.
</P>
<P>
It added that the success of the project will show Nigeria's
"capability of being self-reliant in the production of these
wares without recourse to foreign vendors."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria also plans to end the massive importation of uniform
fabrics and footwear by producing them by itself.
</P>
<P>
The newsletter disclosed that Nigerian manufacturers have
already succeeded in producing some samples.
</P>
<P>
The biggest problem facing the self-reliance efforts is fund,
the newsletter said. It proposed the establishment of a
two-billion-Naira (about 24 million U.S. Dollars) Research Trust
Fund to finance defense research and development projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
