<HEADLINE> Canada's Building Permits Value Up in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The total value of building
permits issued in Canada reached 1.9 billion U.S. dollars in
August, up 2.5 percent from July, Statistics Canada said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In August, residential building intentions gained steam for the
first time in five months, offsetting a slight decline in proposed
non-residential construction.
</P>
<P>
Municipalities in the country issued one billion dollars' worth
of building permits for housing, up 6.4 percent from July, while
the value of non-residential permits fell 1.3 percent to 0.9
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"It was a significant rebound for the housing sector which has
recorded monthly declines since April -- except for a slight
increase during June," the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
The rise in August was due mostly to an increase in the value
of building permits for single-family dwellings, which represent
about 70 percent of the residential sector.
</P>
<P>
The total value of building permits so far this year stands at
14.8 billion dollars, 12.5 percent ahead of the first eight months
of last year, the agency said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
