<HEADLINE> Illegal Weapons Remain in Lesotho: General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of illegal
weapons are floating around in Lesotho after the recent turmoil
in Lesotho, Defense Force chief Lieutenant-General Makhula
Masakeng said in the capital of Maseru Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Retrieving these firearms has become the immediate challenge
facing the country's security forces, South African Press
Association quoted Masakeng as saying.
</P>
<P>
In his first media briefing since his reinstatement after
rebel soldiers deposed him last month, Masakeng said: "What is of
concern to the Lesotho security forces is the weapons stolen from
our armories by some of the mutineers."
</P>
<P>
Robbie Hartslief, a senior officer from the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) peace-keeping troops deployed in the
mountain kingdom, said there were still thousands of illegal
weapons, including AK47 assault rifles in the country.
</P>
<P>
The SADC troops from South Africa and Botswana entered Lesotho
on September 22 to quell rising unrest over alleged
irregularities in the May 23 general elections.
</P>
<P>
They ran into fierce resistance from rebel soldiers who had
rendered Lesotho virtually ungovernable.
</P>
<P>
Issuing a stern warning that the possession of illegal
firearms would not be tolerated, Masakeng urged people with
information of such weapons or arms caches to come forward.
</P>
