<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Global Action to Curb Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Tuesday that concerted global action was needed to resolve
the world financial crisis which was worsening.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that if we act together we can end the present
crisis," Clinton told a joint annual meeting of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Threatening global financial instability and world recession was
centered in the agenda of the meeting, attended by fiance
ministers and central bank governors from member nations at a
Washington hotel.
</P>
<P>
Opening the three-day meeting, Clinton noted that the crisis
has rocked much of Asia and Russia and is now threatening to
damage Brazil and other Latin American nations. Even the U.S.
economy is beginning to feel effects of the crisis with slower job
growth and unstable markets.
</P>
<P>
"We must take urgent steps to help those who have been hurt by
it, to limit the reach of it and to restore confidence in the
global economy."
</P>
<P>
He called for solutions that aim not only at the immediate
crisis but at the longer term. "We must modernize and reform the
international financial system to make it ready for the 21st
century," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president renewed his call for the
Republican-controlled Congress to approve 18 billion U.S. dollars
in U.S. funding for the IMF.
</P>
<P>
"There is no excuse with refusing to supply the fire department
with water while the fire is burning," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also called on Japan to invigorate its economy, largest
in Asia, which has been stuck in a long and steep recession and
deep trouble in its banking system.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed Japan's announcement that it would provide 30
billion U.S. dollars in loan guarantees and other assistance to
other Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, James D. Wolfensohn, president of the World
Bank Group, called for new international architecture beyond a
short-term financial crisis response.
</P>
<P>
"If we do not have the capacity to deal with social
emergencies, if we do not have longer-term plans for solid
institutions, if we do not have greater equity and social justice,
there will be no political stability and without political
stability no amount of money put together in financial packages
will give us financial stability," Wolfensohn said.
</P>
<P>
He called for a reform agenda that addresses issues of
governance and social justice as well as far-reaching corporate and
financial sector reforms.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the World Bank was moving towards a new
"total" approach towards its development work, moving the Bank
"beyond projects" and, in partnership with governments and civil
society, to rigorously pursue the social and structural priorities
needed to champion sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Michel Camdessus, Chairman of the Executive Board and Managing
Director of the International Monetary Fund put forward a five
principles to form a new architecture, including transparency,
soundness of financial systems, involvement of the private sector,
orderly liberalization of capital flows, and modernization of
international markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
