<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana's gold production Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Contrary to a projected slump
in Ghana's gold production and earnings for 1998, the metal's
News Agency (GNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Production returns released by the Mines Department Tuesday,
showed about 20 percent increase in the value of gold produced
between January and June, GNA said in a special report to Xinhua
based in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
From a first half-year value of 260.17 million U.S. Dollars in
1997, Ghana is expected to receive 324.78 million Dollars from
3.05 million ounces of gold produced for the same period this
year.
</P>
<P>
By June 1997, Ghana had produced 718,640 fine ounces and by
December it increased to 1.57 million fine ounces, according to
the Department's tallies.
</P>
<P>
The government, in its 1998 budget, projected a fall in gold
export earnings to 528.6 million Dollars from 1997's 563.7
million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
But, while the projection was based on a preceding bad year
and the falling gold prices on the international bullion market,
domestic volume of gold production has been on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The mining terrain, though, has been turbulent with inadequate
power supply, high tariffs which have swollen the production cost
of the companies and external depressed gold market, most of the
mines have adopted measures to sustain production targets or
increased it.
</P>
<P>
But, analysts have predicted a sloppy third quarter earnings
from a contraction in production levels as a result of the
cumulative effect of the energy crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ghana was plunged into a severe energy shortage for most part
of the year from bad weather which dried up water from its main
hydro-electric dam at Akosombo. Restoring normalcy in power
supply resulted in high tariffs.
</P>
<P>
This, has pushed up the production cost of most mines since
April when the crisis was heightened, from about 228 to 260
dollars an ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Government Starts Controlling Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 6 (Xinhua) -- New Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov on Tuesday evening announced that the Russian
government has been formed and started to take emergency measures
to stabilize the situation.
</P>
<P>
In a television address Primakov emphasized that it is a matter
of creating normal living conditions for Russian citizens.
</P>
<P>
The government will perform obligations to pay monetary
allowances to servicemen and to pay current salaries to all
persons on the state payroll, Primakov said, adding current
pensions will be paid in October, and the payments will be further
done every month.
</P>
<P>
He continued that the government will pay all the debts to
veterans and help regions with the payment of salaries to
teachers, physicians and cultural workers.
</P>
<P>
The most important for Russia at present is to create
conditions for setting the real economy in motion, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the important role of assistance and foreign
investments in industry, agriculture and the infrastructure,
Primakov noted, "we are aware of that the stress should be put on
the development of the domestic production."
</P>
<P>
In his words, the real economy will not start working and
gaining momentum when the banking system is not revived; the clots
in all channels such as nonpayments between the budget and
enterprises and between enterprises themselves are not eliminated
and a taxation system are not set up.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to restructure the whole banking system as soon
as possible, Primakov said. The Central Bank and the government
are separating all the commercial banks into those that can and
must continue operating and those that are to be liquidated, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government intends to make proposals shortly on improving
the taxation system, in particular by reducing the producer's tax
burden, tightening the tax administering system and fighting the
shadow economy, Primakov remarked.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the taxation system must be built so as to
move much of that economy from the shadows and enable it to
operate in line with regulation, with the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
