<HEADLINE> Cohen Opposes Use of Ground Troops in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said on Tuesday he opposed any use of U.S. ground
troops in Kosovo, but warned that NATO air strikes hit Serbs hard
if they do not quickly comply with U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
Testifying before the Senate Armed Services Committee, Cohen
said that the airstrikes by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) could destroy a "substantial portion" of Serbia's military
power.
</P>
<P>
Cohen told the lawmakers that failures to launch such strikes
would assure continued "arrogance" by (Yugoslav President)
Milosevic in ignoring U.N. and NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
However, Cohen said that the U.S. should not provide any ground
troops to the region.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that the United States would supply the
preponderance of air power for any NATO strikes and that any
ground operation should be the responsibility of European nations.
</P>
<P>
Many members of Congress oppose sending U.S. ground troops to
Kosovo because the use of thousands of American and other
peacekeeping troops in Bosnia has continued for more than two
years with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
"We have, I think, a different situation between Kosovo and
Bosnia and I don't believe it would take that kind of a presence
that we have in Bosnia" to secure peace in Kosovo, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
NATO has threatened to launch air strikes against Yugoslavia
unless Belgrade authorities end the conflict with Kosovo Albanian
separatists and negotiates an autonomy agreement with them for the
southern Serbian province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
