<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Surge after Consecutive Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Shares across Europe recovered
strongly Tuesday after falling sharply over the last few days.
</P>
<P>
London shares rebounded after suffering four days of heavy
losses. The FTSE 100, the blue chip share index was up 205.3
points, or more than 3 percent, at 4854.
</P>
<P>
The market was lifted by better performances in Europe and
Tokyo and hopes that the 0.5 percent interest rate cut in Spain
would be reflected by the Bank of England on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen one or two big players, who have been absent of
late, nibbling away," said the head of equity trading at a leading
European investment bank. "There are still some sellers out there
but with the hope of an interest rate cut later in the week, maybe
things will steady up a bit."
</P>
<P>
Bank shares, which have been savaged by fears over the health
of the world economy, were in favour again with Bank of Scotland
shares surging more than 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish central bank reduced its key intervention rate by
0.50 percent to 3.75 percent. The move reduced the difference
between Spanish and German rates, something that will be necessary
before the euro is created in less than three months time.
</P>
<P>
That move, and remarks by the Bundesbank President Hans
Tietmeyer in Washington, spurred hopes that there would be
coordinated interest rate cuts across Europe. He said the
international crisis may make such cuts necessary.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, Germany's Dax ended up over 4 percent at 4815, up
214 points. The strong performance was boosted by Wall Street's
strong opening at the end of the session.
</P>
<P>
German shares also benefited from a strengthening of the
dollar, which would help exporters.
</P>
<P>
But there were still worries for the banking sector, after two
big banks were put on credit watch. Deutsche Bank shares suffered
after the bank forecast weaker profits due to international
turbulence. Paris
</P>
<P>
Paris stocks opened higher on rate cut optimism. The Cac 40
index of leading shares ended up 156 points, or nearly 5 percent,
to 3136, recovering some of its big losses last week.
</P>
<P>
Some of shares which had experienced sharp falls recently, like
Alcatel, continued their recovery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
