<HEADLINE> Clinton: NATO Prepared to Use Force in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Tuesday that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
was prepared to act in Kosovo if Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic did not comply fully with the U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
Clinton gave the warning in a speech to the joint secretariat
meeting of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who spoke to Blair for about 20 minutes on the
telephone about Kosovo Tuesday, said "we all agree that Kosovo is
a powder keg in the Balkans," one that left unchecked could
threaten the stability of other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
"If the violence continues, it could spill over and threaten
the peace and stability of Bosnia, of Albania, of Macedonia and
other countries in the region," said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke, in meetings with
Milosevic, was reiterating that Milosevic must comply with U.N.
demands that he declare an immediate cease-fire, withdraw Serb
forces, give humanitarian relief groups full and immediate access
to Kosovo and begin real negotiations with Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Holbrooke was telling Milosevic that "NATO is
prepared to act" if the Yugoslav president failed to meet the U.N.
demands.
</P>
<P>
"The stakes are high; the time is now to end the violence in
Kosovo. I hope all of you will do whatever you can to that end,"
he told the meeting which focuses on world financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"What is already a humanitarian crisis could turn into a
catastrophe. Some 250,000 people have been forced to flee their
homes. Of that number, approximately 50,000 are actually homeless.
As winter sets in, they risk freezing or starving to death,"
Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
