<HEADLINE> UNITA's Foreign Arms Suppliers Tried in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Angola government has
brought eight foreigners to court for involvement in flying arms
to the opposition National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Eight foreigners were recently tried in a court in Menibgue,
capital of Cuando-Cubango Province in southern Angola for
intruding into the country's air space and supplying arms to
UNITA, the Angolan News Agency Angog reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners -- six South Africans, one Belgian and one
Congolese from Democratic Congo -- were detained after they were
forced to land by the government air planes on January 20 this
year while they were transporting arms to UNITA in southern
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Among them, some were charged for supplying arms and logistics
to UNITA many times and for encroaching on the sovereignty and
security of Angola, and for breaking the United Nations'
sanctions on UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Though four of the eight escaped from prison in August, they
were tried in absentia, a statement from the court said.
</P>
<P>
Arms and mining equipment, all banned by the U.N. sanctions,
were found on their plane after it was forced to land, and they
admitted their destination was to Andulo, an important strategic
city in central Angola controlled by UNITA, for delivering the
equipment to UNITA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
