<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Negotiations in Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Substantive progress has been
made in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations and U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright was encouraged by the "right mood,"
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During her first day of shuttle diplomacy in the region,
the secretary of state experienced "the right mood, right
atmosphere and good will" and she believed these were "enough
(for the Israelis and the Palestinians) to begin making concrete
agreement on various pieces of the U.S. proposal," Rubin said
at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Albright held talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in Jerusalem in the morning and then met with
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat in Jerico in
 the afternoon. She described both meetings as "useful."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Albright was encouraged that both leaders have
got down to business, adding that "substantive progress" has
been made.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman hinted that an agreement on the Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank could be reached during a summit
between Netanyahu, Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton in
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Clinton initiated the summit during a three-way meeting with
Netanyahu and Arafat in Washington last week. There were
reports of progress during that meeting.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who is scheduled to stay in the region till
Wednesday, will try to "lock in" the progress on many issues
during her talks with the two sides, and U.S. Middle East
envoy Dennis Ross and Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk
will "further clear the underbrush," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The scope of the second Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank has been "largely resolved", he said. But he described
the issue of security cooperation between Israel and the
Palestinians as "more complicated."
</P>
<P>
Arafat announced in Washington last week that the
Palestinians would accept the Israeli proposal that Israel
withdraw from 13 percent of the West Bank, as an American
initiative demands, but 3 percent will be a nature reserve
under joint Israeli-Palestinian security control.
</P>
<P>
Rubin declined to confirm or deny reports that the U.S.
and Israel have reached agreement on the security issue and
now it is up to the Palestinians to accept it, saying that
the U.S. is trying to "institutionalize" the security cooperation
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that a three-way meeting between
Albright, Netanyahu and Arafat will be held Wednesday morning.
Some have said that such a meeting will signify that
significant progress has been made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
