<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Basketball Referees Concern IRS Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A special agent for the
Internal Revenue Service believes that U.S. college basketball
referees who gamble may be vulnerable to offers to fix games.
</P>
<P>
"To me, one of the biggest areas of concern is the referees,"
agent Tom Moriarty said. "Are they monitored for gambling?"
</P>
<P>
Moriarty made his remarks last week at a DePaul
University-sponsored sports gambling seminar.
</P>
<P>
"Our office has numerous cases of NBA referees who cash in
their first-class tickets provided by the league to ride coach
and pocket the difference in fares," Moriarty said. "They are
given IRS forms by the league to fill out listing this as taxable
income.
</P>
<P>
"At least nine have not done this and have been prosecuted for
criminal tax evasion. If they do that and jeopardize their
occupations for amounts from $500 to $1,200, what would someone
who has a gambling problem do if he could make $20,000, $40,000
or $80,000 by shaving points in a game?"
</P>
<P>
In all of the U.S. college basketball scandals dating from the
1940s, there never has been an accusation that a referee
influenced the outcome.
</P>
<P>
Every point-shaving incident has involved men's basketball
programs. However, at the DePaul seminar, NCAA agent Bill Saum
cautioned, "We cannot forget about women's athletics in the field
of gambling. It's just a matter of time before unsavory
individuals reach out to our women. People love to wager on what
they see on TV. Now there's a betting line on the entire NCAA
women's tournament." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
