<HEADLINE> China Has Rolls-Royce's Best Joint Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Rolls-Royce's Chairman Sir Ralph
Robins, who is here with British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
said today that XR Aerocomponents Co., Ltd. (XRA), a joint venture
of Rolls-Royce and a company in Xi'an has been very successful and
is probably one of the best of all of Rolls Royce's joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
XRA delivered its first parts for Rolls-Royce last May. The
director of operation for Rolls-Royce said that this showed them
the tremendous potential for collaboration with China.
</P>
<P>
Robins said that XRA's success was not achieved in one day. He
himself has visited China at least once a year since the late
1970's, he explains, and that this is a really big market, a
market of the future.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has looked into the Chinese market of the next
20 years, and wants to occupy 40 percent of the civil aviation
market here.
</P>
<P>
His confidence has not been in the least diminished by the
Asian Financial Crisis, which did seem to hurt the economy on the
continent, but not its attractiveness in the long run.
</P>
<P>
Twelve Chinese airlines now use Rolls-Royce engines on more
than 150 aircraft.  
</P>
</TEXT>
