<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Talks About New UK-China Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair, told a dinner hosted by the British Chamber of Commerce
here this evening, said that a new ear in UK-China relations has
opened.
</P>
<P>
If Britain is to build a new partnership with China, they need
to broaden their efforts, he told those present, and said that the
scale and pace of modernization in China are breathtaking, and
that China will be one of the great economies and political forces
of the next century.
</P>
<P>
He said that a new chapter in commercial relations has also
opened, pointing to Britain's exports to China increasing by 25
percent last year. Britain is by far the largest European investor
in China, with 12 billion pounds of investment pledged, and over
2,000 British joint ventures operating in China, he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had a "very positive discussion" yesterday with
Premier Zhu Rongji on other potential British investments and
contracts worth over 3 billion pounds and that Britain plans to
open a fourth consulate in Chongqing. He announced that there will
be three new projects, worth over 30 million pounds, for improved
health services, prevention of AIDs, and improved water supplies.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was impressed by Chinese leadership's hands-off
approach to Hong Kong and that the British are able to focus not
on concerns about how Hong Kong is run, but on how Hong Kong can
best weather the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Blair also applauded China's measured response to the financial
crisis, saying that China's determination not to devalue the
Chinese yuan has been crucial to stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two countries have reached a broad consensus
on dealing with the crisis, and agreed that analysts and finance
ministers in both countries will work together to address the
issue next month and that China has much to contribute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
