<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, October 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EREZ BORDER CROSSING -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Wednesday that substantial progress has been made
during an extended trilateral meeting with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority Chairman
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Albright announced at a news conference after four hours of
talks with the two leaders that Netanyahu and Arafat will go to
Washington for a summit with U.S. President Bill Clinton on
October 15 in order to complete a deal. (Albright-Netanyahu-Arafat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada warned here
Wednesday that the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
should stick to its commitments to free trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the 30th conference of ASEAN
 economic ministers, Estrada cautioned ASEAN member countries
against "backsliding on free trade commitments," urging these
countries to maintain open markets. (Phillipines-Estrada-ASEAN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The Afghan Taliban militia have invited the
U.N. special envoy on Afghanistan, Lakhdar Brahimi, to visit
Afghanistan for talks rather than inviting the Taliban to
Islamabad, a senior Taliban official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Taliban Interim Council Muhammad Rabbani has sent a
letter to Brahimi, who is currently in Iran, asking him to visit
Kabul for talks with the Taliban leaders, Saeedur Rahman Haqqani,
chief Taliban representative in Islamabad, told Xinhua.
(Pakistan-Taliban-UN Envoy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi Wednesday
called on Turkey and Syria to solve their differences through
political means and to avoid any possible confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to foreign and domestic reporters, Kharrazi said that
Turkey and Syria, as two civilized countries, can solve their
problems peacefully without resorting to military option.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Iran will support Syria in case it is attacked by
Turkey, he said that Iran, as the nation that is holding the
chairmanship of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC),
feels the responsibility to prevent any confrontation.
(Iran-Turkey-Syria)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- The Republic of Singapore Air Force (RSAF)
Wednesday received the delivery of six F-16C/D Fighting Falcons
purchased from the United States, the Ministry of Defense
announced in a news bulletin.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes landed at the Tengah Air Base on the island in
the morning after a 15,973-kilometer journey from Luke Air Force
Base, U.S, and their arrival brings to 10 the total number of the
F-16C/Ds which will constitute RSAF's major fighting force in
recent future, the ministry said. (Singapore-US-Warplanes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
Wednesday ruled out the possibility of a snap general election now
and said that the Barisan Nasional (BN) (National Front)
government has to focus on reviving the economy.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is not necessary to stretch our limited energy
between managing the economy and the elections," Mahathir, who is
chairman of the ruling 14-party BN coalition, said at the closing
of the National Congress on Economic Recovery here Wednesday
evening. (Malaysia-PM-Election)
</P>
