<HEADLINE> France Advises Nationals to Leave Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The French foreign ministry on
Wednesday advised its nationals to leave Yugoslavia because of
possible NATO air strikes over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the ministry also asked French travellers
not to go to Yugoslavia until further notice.
</P>
<P>
The French embassy in Belgrade on Wednesday delivered the
advice to French nationals in Yugoslavia, including the embassy
personnel and their relatives.
</P>
<P>
There are about 1,000 French nationals in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Sweden, the Netherlands and Spain have also urged their
nationals to leave Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has demanded that Yugoslavia withdraw its
forces from Kosovo and end its military action against the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by the French newspaper, Le Monde, on Wednesday,
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said that if Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic did not meet the U.N. requests, NATO
would take action.
</P>
<P>
NATO forces had made all preparations for the air strikes and
the countdown had started, he warned.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac said Tuesday that NATO military
strikes, likely to be decided in coming days, could be avoided if
a ceasefire was reached and Yugoslavia withdrew its troops from
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
