<HEADLINE> Sudan Asks for Clarifications About Mubarak's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Sudan has officially asked
Cairo through diplomatic channels for clarifications about
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's remarks on the potentials of
Al-Shifaa pharmaceutical plant to produce chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Sudanese daily "Al Rai Al Am" quoted Sudanese
Minister of Culture and Information and government spokesman Ghazi
Salah el-Din as saying that Mubarak's remarks have undermined the
credit which the two peoples have built in order to bridge the
gap that hit bilateral relations in the past.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Sudanese National Assembly (parliament) on
Tuesday, the Sudanese minister said that Mubarak's statements do
not match with Egypt's previous attitudes and do not correspond
with the efforts Egypt claims to be making in favor of Sudan's
cause.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Egyptian weekly Al-Ahram's board
chairman and editor-in-chief Ibrahim Nafie on the silver jubilee
of the October 1973 War, Mubarak said that "we know it (the
factory) is a pharmaceutical factory but it is capable of
producing ingredients for chemical weapons. There is another
chemical factory close to it."
</P>
<P>
El-Din also indicated that Sudanese Foreign Minister Mustafa
Osman Ismail, during a recent meeting with his Egyptian
counterpart Amr Moussa, had also called for clarifications.
</P>
<P>
He said that such statements might justify the American
aggression against the pharmaceutical factory which was destroyed
by American missiles on August 20 on the grounds that it produced
chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return to Khartoum from Cairo Tuesday, Ismail stated
that he had had a meeting with Moussa, adding that Sudan and Egypt
were in the process of making plans to normalize relations between
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
