<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Ends Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri Wednesday wrapped up his three-day visit to Saudi
Arabia, during which he discussed with Saudi leaders Arab and
Islamic issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in Riyadh said Hariri, who met with Saudi King Fahd
Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Second Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Defense and Aviation Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz, discussed with
them the current dispute between Syria and Turkey, Kuwait News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Tensions are mounting between Damascus and Ankara after they
traded accusations against each other, and Turkey reportedly
threatened to resort to military option against Syria. Turkey
accused Syria of harboring and supporting the Kurdish Workers'
Party rebels fighting for autonomy in southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria has lashed out at Turkey, a predominantly Muslim
country, for forming military alliance with Israel, which it says
is targeted against the Arab world, especially itself, and
undermines its bargaining position in negotiations with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Syria has disputes with Israel over the future of the Golan
Heights, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war. Damascus
insists on its return as a condition for peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Hariri also discussed the Middle East peace
process which stalled for 18 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
