<HEADLINE> Russia, Greece Agree to Cooperate in Handling Turkish-Syrian Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Greece agreed Wednesday to
cooperate in dealing with strained relations between Turkey and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference after talks with his Greek
counterpart Akis Tsohatzopoulos, Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev described the recent escalation of tension in relations
between Turkey and Syria as "a serious issue."
</P>
<P>
He said Russia and Greece had agreed to study all aspects of
relations between Turkey and Syria through the exchange of
information and analyses on a permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
There was a high risk of the problems getting worse because of the
launching of threats and lesser importance being attached to their
peaceful settlement, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that he would fly to Damascus to discuss the
matter with Syrian leaders.
</P>
<P>
While expressing concern at the escalation in tension between
Turkey and Syria, Tsohatzopoulos urged the international community to
send the message to Ankara that Turkey's threats to use force in
resolving its disputes with Syria and its incursion into northern Iraq
were "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
As for Turkey's threats to prevent Cyprus from installing the
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, Tsohatzopoulos said that as
U.N. members, both Greece and Cyprus were exercising their inalienable
right to implement a joint defense policy against a foreign threat.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Sergeyev said that they were very careful in all their
movements from the viewpoint of international law.
</P>
<P>
Both ministers agreed during their talks to promote policies of
collective security to confront crisis in the greater area of the
Black Sea and the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev is currently in Greece for a two-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
