<HEADLINE> Stopping Chinese Army, Armed Police, and Government Businesses (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), the State Council, and the Central
Military Commission held a meeting October 6-7 where it was
decided that the Chinese Army, the Armed Police, and law
enforcement offices can no longer be involved in business
activities.
</P>
<P>
Hu Jintao, a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and a member of the
Secretariat of the CPC Central Committee, told the meeting that
the central authorities made this decision two months ago and
that it had the wholehearted support of the Party, the military,
and the people.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was presided over by Wei Jianxing, Standing
Committee member of the Political Bureau and secretary of the CPC
Central Commission for Discipline Inspection.
</P>
<P>
The CPC Central Committee places great importance on this, Hu
said, and that President Jiang Zemin, who is also general
secretary of the CPC Central Committee, had asked these groups to
separate themselves from all businesses established by subsidiary
units, and that the state will ensure the necessary expenditures
of the military, the Armed Police, and law enforcement offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
