<HEADLINE> Sino-British Satellite Research Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- China's Qinghua University and
Britain's Surrey University signed an agreement for a joint
venture to develop small satellites here today that was attended
by Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
Qinghua, which is one of China's major university, has
announced that it will launch a small satellite, the "Tsinghua-1",
by the end of 1999 and that a new company will be responsible for
controlling "Tsinghua-1" and developing other satellites.
</P>
<P>
Smaller light-weight satellites have been widely used in
communications, monitoring environmental changes and natural
disasters, and in scientific experiments in space.
</P>
<P>
The Tsinghua-1 is 1.2 meters high and weighs 75 kilograms. It
will be the first of seven satellites forming a Sino-British
satellite network to monitor natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Qinghua University will send a team to Britain this month to
design and do tests on the Tsinghua-1.
</P>
<P>
The universities also established the Tsinghua-Surrey Small
Satellite Research Center last month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
