<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Acts to Reduce Emission From Burning Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Wednesday that it had proposed regulation on the incineration of
waste to limit the emission of dangerous pollutants.
</P>
<P>
The proposed regulation aimed at reducing total emission of
dioxins and furants from the burning of municipal waste, clinical
waste and sewage sludge to approximately 11 grams per year by
2005.
</P>
<P>
The aim is expected to be achieved even with the expected
increase in the amount of waste incinerated.
</P>
<P>
This would mean a reduction in excess of 99 percent relative to
the 1994 level, according to commission officials.
</P>
<P>
Emissions to air from the incineration of clinical and
municipal wastes are now approximately 2,300 grams per year in the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
The burning of waste has been identified as the largest known
source of emission of dioxins and furants to air in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Dioxin is supposed to be the most toxic man-made substance.
The most toxic is a known human carcinogen. The compounds produce
chloracne at high exposures and a wide range of non-cancer effects
are thought to occur at extremely low levels of chronic exposure,
including adverse effects on reproduction, impacts on the
development of the unborn foetus and associations with impaired
mental ability.
</P>
<P>
Recent studies estimated that emission from waste burning
account for 36,000 kilograms per year of mercury and 16,000
kilograms per year of cadmium in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The full implementation of the commission proposed regulation
on waste burning should reduce the total estimated emissions of
mercury and cadmium from incineration to 7,100 kilograms per year
and to 1,100 kilograms per year respectively.
</P>
<P>
Exposure to mercury has been found to affect the nervous system
and the kidneys and may cause foetal damage while cadmium exposure
has been associated to lung cancer and kidney damage.
</P>
<P>
The amount of municipal waste incinerated in the 15-nation
European Union is expected to increase from 31 million tons per
year in 1990 to 56.5 million tons per year in 2004. The costs
were estimated to be around 550 million ECU (605 million U.S.
dollars) per year at the time being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
