<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ozone Hole Is Bigger And Deeper Ever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Earth's ozone hole over
Antarctic has swollen to an all-time record and got into
stratosphere deeper, the Washington Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Satellite and weather balloons measured the total area of ozone
depletion at 10.5 million square miles, larger than all of North
America. That's nearly a third larger than last year, and about
5 percent bigger than the previous record set in 1996.
</P>
<P>
This year's ozone hole is also unusually deep, extending
nearly 15 miles into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
A thin band of ozone high above Earth protects the planet
from the most harmful ultraviolet rays from the sun. This
radiation can destroy plants and cause cataracts and skin cancer
in human. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
