<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Will Be Country Of Elderly By 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- By the year 2000, there will be
130 million people 60 or older in China, or ten percent of the
population, according to Zhang Wenfan, president of the China
Association for the Elderly.
</P>
<P>
China has the largest number of elderly now, at 120 million, a
fifth of the world's total, Zhang told a symposium on aging in
northeastern Asian countries today.
</P>
<P>
And that number is expected to be above 400 million by the year
2050, or 1 out of every 4 Chinese a senior citizen.
</P>
<P>
China is experiencing a much faster change to an elderly
society than many industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
The number of elderly has been growing by 3.2 percent per year
since the 1980s, he said, and the number of people over 80 keeps
increasing as life expectancy gets longer.
</P>
<P>
And, this has caused many problems. Traditional methods of
caring for the elderly depended solely on family members, but are
difficult to apply now because the family is becoming smaller, the
young people in rural areas move to cities, more females have
jobs, and so on, he said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium has Chinese, Japanese and Korean
specialists discussing new methods of combining family-based
caring and community service to provide a better life for the
elderly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
