<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Central Bank Chief Rejects Calls for Rate Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany's central bank president,
Hans Tietmeyer, has reiterated his opposition to a cut in the
country's interest rates as hoped by many financial experts to
help avert a possible global economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German Die Zeit newspaper, Tietmeyer
said that European interest rates must first converge at the
German levels ahead of the formal launch of the single European
currency on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the recent cut in U.S. interest rates was
not a model for Germany.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. rates are over five percent. Ours are a little bit above
3.0 percent. Nobody can truly hope that we take the Americans as a
model interest-rate level," Tietmeyer said.
</P>
<P>
European economies have seen no major impact from the financial
crises in Asia and Russia so far. But international financial
experts argue that Europe cannot not escape a global slowdown in
the long run.
</P>
<P>
Under increasing pressure for a rate cut, Tietmeyer said
earlier this week in Washington that the German central bank would
only move if the global economic crisis worsened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
