<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Vietnam Sign Two Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Vietnam Wednesday
signed agreements on Judicial cooperation and narcotics
suppression.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement on legal and judicial cooperation, Thailand
will help prepare curricula and methodology for the training of
Vietnamese judges.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also calls for exchanges of lawyers and of legal
texts promulgated in the respective countries, as well as the
setting up of a joint working group comprising governmental and
non-government agencies.
</P>
<P>
The agreement for cooperation in the suppression of narcotics,
to be implemented by the Office of the Narcotics Control Board of
Thailand and Vietnam's National Drugs Control Committee, provides
for cooperation in the control of narcotics crops, psychotropic
substances and precursor chemicals, law enforcement, and exchange
of information on existing laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also calls for cooperation in the prevention of
drug abuse, and rehabilitation of addicts.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese President Tran Duc Luong began his three-day visit
to Thailand Tuesday. He Wednesday met with Thai Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai and Parliament Speaker Wan Muhamad Nor Matha, and
Thai businessmen to discuss boosting bilateral trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between Thailand and Vietnam reached 759 million
U.S. dollars in 1997 and 599 million U.S. dollars in the first
eight months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is Vietnam's ninth largest foreign investor with 78
projects worth 1.1 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Reduce Restrictions on Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Economic ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) Wednesday signed an
agreement to remove restrictions on investment to make the region
more attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN Secretary General Rodolfo Severino, attending the two-day
ASEAN economic minister meeting which began Wednesday, said the
agreement to set up an "ASEAN Investment Area" will make it easier
for investors in one country to invest in other countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, national treatment, which means
both local and foreign investors will be treated in the same way,
will be extended to ASEAN investors by 2010 and to all other
investors by 2020.
</P>
<P>
All industries will be opened to outside investors, except
those that affect national security and public morals, those
relating to the protection of human, animal or plant life and
those necessary to comply with laws to protect the public.
</P>
<P>
In case of serious imbalance of payments and financial woes, an
ASEAN country is allowed to impose investment restrictions, but
the restrictions must be "temporary and should not harm other
ASEAN nations," the agreement said.
</P>
<P>
Each country can also draw up a list of investment areas or
industries that can not be opened up immediately. But the list
must be phased out by 2010, except for Laos, Myanmar and Vietnam,
ASEAN's most recent members.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the economic ministers also signed an
agreement under which ASEAN nations will notify each other of any
changes in trade policies, including tariffs, quotas, surcharges,
customs valuation, export taxes and foreign exchange controls.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China Makes Headway in Investment System Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Writer Qian Yuhong
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- China has two venture funds for
small businesses that are considered a significant part of its
investment system reforms, with high return and high risk referred
to as a kind of "risk investment", that is more efficient than
investments of the planned economy.
</P>
<P>
They will be used specifically to develop new technology to
perfect the industrial mix, according to an economist with the
Ministry of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's highest governing body, has decided
to put 3 billion yuan into the two funds, with hopes of initiating
risk investment.
</P>
<P>
Inefficient, poorly managed investment have been a major
headache for the Chinese government, which used to be the sole
investor and decision maker under the planned economy, so it began
the investment reforms in 1978 and set up a new system more
oriented to the market economy in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The reforms include improved controls, separating commercial
loans from policy-oriented loans through a State Development Bank,
and adopting a responsibility system and have resulted in more
investors, diverse funding, and more scientific investment.
</P>
<P>
Fixed assets investment also grew from 1980 to 1997, with 14.16
trillion yuan for 763,588 projects.
</P>
<P>
However, economists point out that the reform of China's
investment system is still stunted by the planned economy. The
nation also lacks an efficient management system to supervise
investments and needs to increase market reforms for investment,
economists say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Court Hears "Case" in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A British moot court case that
was heard in Beijing today was attended by Chinese and British
members of the legal professional, journalists, and briefly by the
British prime minister's wife who is visiting China along with the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
It was part of British Law Week and showed a trial of the Queen
vs. John Hotfoot who was accused of being the driver of a getaway
car for three armed robbers. He contended that he was forced to
drive them at gunpoint while he was just waiting for his mother on
the street. The robbers were still at large.
</P>
<P>
The judge was Lord Justice Otton of the Court of
Appeals. Prosecution and defense council were provided by two
members of the Queen's Council, and the jury was made up of 12
Chinese legal experts.
</P>
<P>
This interesting exchange can help people understand each other
better, according to Yan Junxing, president of the Chinese
Ministry of Justice's Judicial Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
"China introduced several major reforms to its legal system in
recent years, like establishing the principle of presumption of
innocence and statutory crimes and punishments, which are elements
of Anglo-American laws," he said. China's legal system is getting
closer to the British in certain aspects, but China is weak in the
execution and implementation of laws, he explains, adding that the
Chinese legal community will benefit a lot from this meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Court Hears "Case" in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Today's moot court shows some flaws in the British legal system
that need improvement, Yan said. For example, the defendant has no
right to argue for himself, and the fact that lawyers have too big
a role to play is likely to result in an unfair verdict because of
the different abilities of lawyers, he added.
</P>
<P>
And, long, drawn out hearings obviously put a financially-weak
defendant at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
Lord Justice Otton, who was the judge, said that the British
and Chinese legal systems have their own characteristics and that
the purpose of the moot court was to show how the British system
works, not to ask the hosts to follow the British example.
</P>
<P>
The British legal system is also changing as more British
courts try to solve business disputes and other cases out of the
court through mediation, arbitration and reconciliation, which are
widely practiced in China.
</P>
<P>
One British diplomat commented that if the British people
understand more about Chinese law and the legal system they will
probably be more interested in investing in China and the same is
true about the Chinese and British law. Cooperation and exchanges
in legal affairs between the two countries can promote economic,
trade and technological cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The moot court hearing will be broadcast later by television and
radio stations in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
