<HEADLINE> Palestinian Urges Effective U.S. Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat Wednesday called for effective mediation from Washington to
broker a deal over Israeli troops redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Time is running out (for the U.S.) to arrange something on the
ground," Erekat said in a telephone interview with the Egyptian
Voice of Arabs Radio.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came as U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
is on a two-day mission in the Mideast to try to narrow the gaps
between the Palestinians and Israel ahead of a mid-October
Washington summit, which is designed to complete a deal on Israeli
troops withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
On table is a U.S. initiative, which calls on Israel to hand
back 13 percent more of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which initially rejected the formula, proposed to hand
over 10 percent and turn the other 3 percent into a nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
After talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton last month in
Washington, Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat
accepted the Israeli proposal.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, then, invited Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to return to Washington in mid-October to
complete a deal.
</P>
<P>
But Erekat said that so far Albright "has not provided the
Palestinian side with any Israeli commitment to implement the
U.S. initiative."
</P>
<P>
According to Erekat, shortly before his meeting with Albright,
Netanyahu decided that Israel would press ahead with plans to set
up a new settlement neighborhood in Arab areas.
</P>
<P>
"It is something that underlines Israel's determination to foil
the peace drive. Israel is the party which undermines and thwarts
the peace process because of its unilateral measures," he
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
