<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Still Not Decided on Action in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- NATO said on Wednesday that the
western military alliance was "fully ready" and the "next
decision" would be on activating the air strikes it menaced for
quite some time.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official, speaking on condition of anonymity, told the
press that the allies were expecting an action order in the next
few days after the 16 NATO member states have reached consensus on
the legality and military objectives of the action to be taken.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the decision could be made in the next 48
hours, the official said that NATO was not prescribing a deadline
for its action.
</P>
<P>
But NATO officials and statesmen from major western countries
have kept saying that time is running out for Slobodan Milosevic
and that he'd better comply fully with the United Nations Security
Council Resolutions (UNSCRs).
</P>
<P>
The same official said that NATO countries are now going
through the democratic process of getting parliamentary and
governmental approvals before the allies could get the consensus
for its go-ahead decision.
</P>
<P>
He said that the key for the turn-on of the green light from
member states was the conviction that Belgrade had not complied
with the UNSCRs, especially the Resolution 1199 adopted on
September 23. The resolution calls for an immediate ceasefire and
an entry to peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia still has 14,000 regular
troops and 11,000 military police force remaining in Kosovo,
compared with 36,000 troops and police forces there 10 days ago,
according to the official who added that NATO estimated that 15
percent of the civilian housing in Kosovo had been damaged by the
Serbian forces in the past month.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the extent of the potential NATO intervention
in Kosovo, the official said that the allies were ready for the
air strikes but were still looking at plans for limited ground
deployment after the cease-fire to maintain the peace.
</P>
<P>
"No decision has been taken yet as regards ground deployment,"
said the official.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations on Tuesday discussed U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's status quo report on Kosovo but stopped short of
giving a mandate for the use of force by NATO in the region.
</P>
<P>
While answering what would be the legal basis for NATO action
if there is no U.N. resolution to that effect, the official said
that a collective understanding on the part of the 16 NATO member
states would offer the allies a sort of legal basis they all feel
comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
The consensus was growing, said the official.
</P>
<P>
It would be a new departure for NATO to find for its actions in
non-NATO countries the legality by way of reaching consensus. In
1995, NATO waited for U.N. resolutions before intervening in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The NATO official told the press that irreversibility was the
key in deciding NATO actions. Actions have to be resorted to if
there is no other alternative, said the official.
</P>
<P>
But he added that ultimate diplomatic push was being given to
both the Serbians and the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The official could not confirm whether United States Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright would make a trip to Brussels to
attend a planned ministerial meeting of NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports quoted NATO sources as saying that the trip had
been called off and there might not be the meeting scheduled for
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
What the official confirmed was that NATO was looking forward
to the outcome for the next emergency meeting of the six-nation
Contact Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
