<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 70 Percent of Tobacco-related Deaths to Occur by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco-related deaths in
developing countries by the 2020s will rise from 50 to 70
percent, according to a report obtained Thursday from the office
of the U.N. Development Program (UNDP)'s resident
representative in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The publication entitled "Human Development Report 1998" and
prepared by UNDP cited the World Health Organization (WHO)'s
estimate which indicates that 3.5 million people die annually
from causes related to tobacco use at present, but by the 2020s
the death toll is likely to reach 10 million each year.
</P>
<P>
In both industrial and developing countries, half of regular
smokers die from causes related to their tobacco use, said the
228-page report, adding that smokers are three times as likely to
die between the ages of 35 and 69 as are non-smokers.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP report also pointed out that since 1970s, most
industrial countries which register half of the tobacco-related
deaths at present have mounted anti-smoking campaigns while in
most developing countries the marketing and advertising campaigns
of tobacco have intensified.
</P>
<P>
Per capita cigarette consumption fell by 10 percent between
the early 1970s and early 1990s in industrial countries, but in
the same period consumption increased by 64 percent in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
What's more, per capita consumption more than doubled in
Haiti, Indonesia, Nepal, Senegal and Syria while tripled in
Cameroun and China in the same period, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
