<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Police Make Largest Seizure of Pirated CDs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 7 (Xinhua) --Singapore police seized 450,000
pieces of pirated CDs in a single joint raid against a syndicate
Tuesday and the seizure was the largest it ever hunted down under
the Copyright Act to date, the police said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The seizure has a market value of 5.4 million Singapore dollars
(3.24 million U.S. dollars), it added.
</P>
<P>
The police said its Criminal Investigation Department (CID)
busted the major local syndicate engaged in importation and
distribution of pirated CD-ROM's, VCDs and CDs and arrested 18
suspects. But it did not identify the syndicate.
</P>
<P>
The CID conducted the joint operation on information received
and raided the syndicate's covert storage points and retail
outlets at a number of places, the police said, adding the
operation was carried out with the help from a number of
governmental and non-governmental organs.
</P>
<P>
In addition to pirated CDs, the police said, an assortment of
unused inlays, jewel boxes, documents evidencing orders, sales and
delivery were recovered.
</P>
<P>
Under laws of Singapore, persons found guilty of selling or
distributing infringing articles of a work in which copyright
subsists, are liable to a fine of up to 100,000 Singapore dollars
(60,000 U.S. dollars) or to a prison term of up to five years or
to both. 
</P>
</TEXT>
