<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Nationals to Leave Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Wednesday ordered its
nationals to leave Yugoslavia immediately as the prospect of NATO
air strikes loomed.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokeswoman said the warning went out on the
British Broadcasting Corporation's World Service on Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
"We advise against travel to the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
(FRY) and we also advise British nationals in the FRY to leave
immediately," the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
However, she declined to say whether the warning to Britons
meant Western military action was imminent, saying the warning was
a "precautionary" measure.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has demanded that Yugoslavia withdraw its
forces from Kosovo and end its military action against the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, France on Wednesday also asked its nationals to
leave Yugoslavia as Western leaders again warned of possible NATO
air strikes over Kosovo. 
</P>
