<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computers in Alberta Unprepared for Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The millennium computer bug is
set to cause chaos in the Canadian province of Alberta because of
the provincial government's failure to tackle the problem, a
senior official has warned.
</P>
<P>
The bug could raise serious risks in the health-care system if
it causes a shutdown in medical equipment and computer systems
after January 1, 2000, provincial Auditor-General Peter Valentine
said in his annual report released on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Valentine warned that other essential services, such as power,
gas and telecommunications were also threatened.
</P>
<P>
The government and other organizations such as the disaster
services branch need to quickly identify the risks and develop
contingency plans to protect Albertans, whose safety could be in
jeopardy, Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
The Year 2000 problem refers to the chaos that computer experts
believe will occur on January 1, 2000. Many computer systems use
only two digits to identify the year which could lead them to
assume that 2000 is 1900 and malfunction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
