<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Hopes for Further Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Prime Minister Tony
Blair said he hopes for close cooperation between Britain and
China to jointly further the reform of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Blair made the remark here earlier today while addressing the
opening ceremony of the "Reform of State-Owned Enterprises -- UK
and Chinese Experience" seminar, jointly sponsored by the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences (CASS), the Great Britain-China Center,
and the British Ministry of Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Blair said both Britain and China face the need to modernize
their economies to cope with the challenges of the new world
economy and improve the lives of their people.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that the participants will have a good
exchange of views, demonstrating bilateral mutual trust and
friendship, and that the seminar will lead to more cooperation and
mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 representatives from government departments, research
institutions and enterprises are attending the two-day seminar.
</P>
<P>
President of the CASS Li Tieying said this is a good
opportunity for scholars, government departments and enterprises
of the two sides to engage in broad discussions to promote mutual
understanding and friendship.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Blair then took part in meetings via live
satellite link with participants at an ongoing international
financial seminar in Wuhan, and "face to face" with several staff
members of a Britain-invested project in the Suzhou Industrial
Park. He also declared the inauguration of a Sino-British joint
venture in Shekou in south China's Shenzhen Special Economic Zone,
also via the satellite link.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Prime Minister Blair met with representatives
attending a Sino-Britain Petrochemical Cooperation Seminar and
"British Law Week" here this morning, and attended a document
exchange ceremony for Sino-British cooperative projects.
</P>
<P>
These projects include a coal-burning power plant in Changsha
costing more than 700 million U.S. dollars funded solely by the
British National Power Company, two water-supply projects in
Guiyang with an investment of 25 million U.S. dollars from the
China Water Company Limited, and the establishment of SmithKline
Beecham (China) Investment Company Ltd., as well as a
micro-satellite technology cooperation project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
