<HEADLINE> Singapore Gets 6 More F-16C/D Warplanes from U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Singapore Air
Force (RSAF) Wednesday received the delivery of six F-16C/D
Fighting Falcons purchased from the United States, the Ministry of
Defense announced in a news bulletin.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes landed at the Tengah Air Base on the island in
the morning after a 15,973-kilometer journey from Luke Air Force
Base, U.S, and their arrival brings to 10 the total number of the
F-16C/Ds which will constitute RSAF's major fighting force in
recent future, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The Six F-16C/Ds are the second batch of delivery of the 18
aircraft which the RSAF purchased in 1994 from the U.S. The first
batch of four F-16C/Ds returned to Singapore in August.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Defense said the rest of the squadron will
return shortly.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the RSAF placed another order for 12 more F-16C/Ds
last year and the order will augment RSAF's F-16C/D force to 30
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and the U.S. reached an agreement in 1996 that the
RSAF's F-16C/D training program, which is planned to end at 2003,
will be extended to 2018. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
