<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Nuclear Power Station Sets Safety Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Daya Bay Nuclear Power
Station in south China's Shenzhen has been setting records for
both safety and power output since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
By October 6, the N0. 2 power generator at the station had
operated continuously for 265 days since its latest overhaul.
</P>
<P>
This was the longest recorded non-stop operation at the station
since it was put into operation in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The station stopped the operation of two generators for
refueling and overhauling at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
By October 6, the nuclear power station had supplied ten
billion kwh of power for the local power grid, setting a record
for power generation for that period.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong-Guangdong joint venture nuclear power station has
already repaid half of its construction loans.
</P>
<P>
This was the first nuclear power station in China that used
overseas funds for construction. Total investment in the station
was four billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
