<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Foreign Currency Reserves Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korean foreign currency
reserves hit 15 billion U.S. dollars at the end of September,
compared to only 4.5 billion U.S. dollars last year, said the Bank
of Korea Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 94 percent of the reserves is corporate savings while 700
million dollars, or six percent, are deposits by individuals.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-eight percent was deposited with local commercial banks,
eight percent with foreign bank branches and four percent with
special financial institutions such as the Korea Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Korea attributed the sharp increase of foreign
reserves to capital inflows from corporate asset sales and the
narrowing gap in interest rates between South Korean won deposits
and foreign currency deposits.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise has contributed a great deal to keeping the
won-dollar exchange rate stable.
</P>
<P>
However, some analysts said the rise is indication that
business concerns may be trying to hold hard currency for fear of
a second foreign exchange crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Peaceful Solution to Turkey-Syria Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Wednesday called on Turkey and Syria to solve their
differences through political means and to avoid any possible
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to foreign and domestic reporters, Kharrazi said that
Turkey and Syria, as two civilized countries, can solve their
problems peacefully without resorting to military option.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Iran will support Syria in case it is attacked by
Turkey, he said that Iran, as the nation that is holding the
chairmanship of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC),
feels the responsibility to prevent any confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Ankara and Damascus have deteriorated
recently after Turkey accused Syria of supporting Turkish Kurdish
rebels fighting for independence.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Turkey has stepped up military buildup
along its border with Syria and some officials even said the two
countries have entered a state of undeclared war.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that he has contacted with foreign ministers of
the two countries, and Iran will help the two countries solve
their disputes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he criticized Ankara for concluding military pacts
with Israel and urged it to reconsider its policy on military
cooperation with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Arab and Islamic countries have condemned and worried about the
growing military alliance between Turkey and Israel, and regarded
it as a real threat to security in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
The OIC summit in Tehran last December called on all the member
states to review their relations with Israel, he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to possible Israeli threat to Iran, Kharrazi said
that Iran will strongly respond to any threat to its interest and
the Israelis know how strongly Iran will react.
</P>
<P>
On a question about the need of nuclear balance in the region,
he said that Iran advocates to declare the region a zone free of
nuclear and any other weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
All nuclear weapons around the world should be destroyed, he
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
