<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Wants to Defuse Tension with Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said on Wednesday that Iran hopes to solve the tension
with the Afghan Taliban militia through diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that without the need to use force, the Taliban would
submit to the demands of the international community and Iran" to
punish the killers, return the bodies of other three slain
Iranians, and release all captured Iranians, Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference here that Iran hoped to solve the
issue through diplomatic means and welcomed the visit to the
region of Lakhdar Brahimi, the special envoy of the U.N. Secretary
General on Afghan affairs.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi arrived here Sunday in an effort to defuse the tension
between Iran and the Taliban triggered by the killing of Iranian
diplomats and reporter in northern Afghanistan in August.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Iran waits to see if the Taliban would be brought
to the terms of the international community.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have returned the bodies of six Iranian diplomats
and reporter, but the whereabouts of the bodies of the three
others were still unknown.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, over 30 Iranian drivers and aid
workers, accused of shipping supplies to the opposition forces,
are still held in the Taliban's prisons.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Brahimi's visit was not the only effort by the
international community, but it was the most important one and
Iran hopes the visit would be successful.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent withdrawal of a group of Iranian
diplomats from Pakistan, Kharrazi reiterated that they were
recalled because of the insecure situation there.
</P>
<P>
Iran, predominated by Shiite Muslims, said its diplomats faced
serious terrorist threats in Pakistan, which has an overwhelming
Sunni Muslim population. Their relations tumbled because Islamabad
supported the Taliban and Tehran backed its rival, the Northern
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
However, Kharrazi said Iran hopes its move would not be seen as
a sign of any change in bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Want U.N. Envoy to Visit Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
have invited the U.N. special envoy on Afghanistan, Lakhdar
Brahimi, to visit Afghanistan for talks rather than inviting the
Taliban to Islamabad, a senior Taliban official said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Taliban Interim Council Muhammad Rabbani has sent a
letter to Brahimi, who is currently in Iran, asking him to visit
Kabul for talks with the Taliban leaders, Saeedur Rahman Haqqani,
chief Taliban representative in Islamabad, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"I had handed over the letter to the acting chief of the U.N.
Special Mission to Afghanistan, James Ngobi, in Islamabad, who had
delivered the message to Brahimi in Tehran," Haqqani said.
</P>
<P>
Ngobi said here Monday that Brahimi has invited high-ranking
Taliban officials for talks. Brahimi has no plan to visit
Afghanistan because of general embargo on U.N. officials by
Secretary General Kofi Annan to visit the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
"We are responsible for Brahimi's security and I am ready to
travel with him in plane during his trip to Afghanistan," Haqqani
said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi is scheduled to arrive in Islamabad Thursday after
concluding his four-day visit to Iran.
</P>
<P>
The recent Six plus Two (Afghanistan's six immediate neighbors
plus the U.S. and Russia) meeting in New York had mandated Brahimi
to visit the region amid growing tension between Iran and
Afghanistan over the killing of nine Iranian diplomats in the
northern Afghan town of Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Haqqani said he believed that Pakistan also wanted Brahimi to
visit Afghanistan. He quoted Pakistan's Foreign Office spokesman
Tariq Altaf as saying that Brahimi's mission would be incomplete
unless he visits Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Ngobi said that Brahimi's trip to Pakistan would mainly focus
on the Iran-Afghan tension. He is scheduled to hold meetings with
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
