<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada: ASEAN Should Stick to Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada warned here Wednesday that the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) should stick to its commitments to free
trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the 30th conference of ASEAN
economic ministers, Estrada cautioned ASEAN member countries
against "backsliding on free trade commitments," urging these
countries to maintain open markets.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative that we maintain this course of continued
integration of our economies within ASEAN and the continued
integration of ASEAN with the rest of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that ASEAN's thrust is to promote a "freer flow of
goods and services, investments and capital," warning against
reneging on commitments to trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
"Given the interdependence of trading nations, backsliding on
our commitments would give out the wrong signals to our trading
partners -- weakening the links we have forged among ourselves and
disrupting harmonious alliance," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the same speech, President Estrada also called on the Group
of Seven to provide the leadership needed to bail Southeast Asia
out of the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"A fast ASEAN turnaround can not be accomplished without the
concerted commitments of the G-7" which includes Britain, Canada,
France, Italy, Germany, Japan and the United States, Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
The seven richest nations "can help contain the current
financial turmoil" by generating economic activities, maintaining
open markets and sustaining credit to the most seriously affected
economies.
</P>
<P>
Estrada urged the United States and other rich nations to make
available their share in the recapitalization of the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting which began Wednesday, the economic
ministers will consider drastic tariff cuts as a pill to revive
the economies hit by Asian financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
