<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Inflation Dips to 9.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's inflation rate dipped
slightly to 9.2 percent for the first nine months of this year, a
0.2 percent fall from the same period of 1997, according to the
latest figures released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The drop indicated that the Thai government has managed to keep
most prices down or stable while the economy entered into
recession this year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation has been kept under the 10 percent target set by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) as a condition for its
17.2-billion-U.S.-dollar bailout package for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is expected to contract at
least 8 percent in 1998, but the government has won praises for
implementing financial reforms, stabilizing the currency baht,
achieving a current account surplus and bringing bank interest
rates down, a Thai cabinet report said.
</P>
<P>
Prices of jasmine rice, vegetables, some fruits, chicken eggs
and fuel all fell in the first three quarters of 1998, while
prices of electricity, cooking gas, bus fares, telephone fees and
clothing remained stable compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
But the first three quarters saw a rise in prices of meat,
fish, tap water, health care and expressway fees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
