<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian, European Countries Offer Counter-Trade Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Several countries in Asia and
Europe have offered to do business with Indonesia using the
counter-trade system, a senior official told Antara News Agency
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Many countries are offering the counter-trade deals to
Indonesia, and this system could become an alternative way during
the economic crisis," Director General of Foreign Trade at the
Trade and Industry Ministry Djoko Moeljono said.
</P>
<P>
He said that companies in India and China were willing to
supply drugs while firms in South Korea were prepared to send raw
materials for shoe-making to Indonesia. Vietnam has also agreed to
become a rice supplier to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
European countries such as Belgium, Austria and France had
offered plane spare parts to national flag-carrier Garuda and to
Merpati airlines.
</P>
<P>
"But most of the commodities the foreign parties want in return
are also in great demand in Indonesia and have a high export price
so that the offers are hard to meet," Moeljono said.
</P>
<P>
For instance, India and China wanted crude palm oil, South
Korea and European countries oil and liquefied natural gas, and
Vietnam urea-based fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
Most of the goods the foreign companies want from Indonesia are
urgently needed by Indonesia itself to stabilize the domestic
market prices of those goods, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Executes Two Smugglers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- China's Supreme People's Court
announced judgement on three smuggling cases today and two
smugglers, Zou Weiquan and Chen Baoquan, were executed today in
South China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jiachen, vice president of the Supreme People's Court said,
"This most serious punishment shows China's strong attitude
against smuggling."
</P>
<P>
A nationwide anti-smuggling campaign by the central government
began this July, and the announcement of the three cases is a
part of this campaign.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, Zou Weiquan, manager of the Hong Kong Jinfeng
Trade Corporation, in collusion with Chen Baoquan, smuggled goods
including household appliances and cars worth 38 million yuan
(about 5 million U.S. dollars), through Guangdong and Huangpu
Customs 17 times, and evaded taxes of 16 million yuan (about 2
million U.S. dollars). Zou also bribed members of the Customs
staff with 985,000 HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that the Supreme People's Court reviewed the judgement
of the Guangdong Intermediate Court and was convinced that Zou and
Chen had committed these crimes. They were then sentenced to
death.
</P>
<P>
The other two cases announced today involved police chief
Wen Guobin of the Yunfu Security Bureau of Guangdong Province
and Hong Kong businessman Zhou Shaoquan.
</P>
<P>
Wen, who gave a green light to smuggling and obtained bribes of
105,000 yuan, was given a life sentence and deprived of political
rights for life.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, in collusion with Bu Lu, a captain of the Dongguan
Navigation Bureau in Guangdong, smuggled 28 cars worth more than 6
million yuan (about 0.8 million U.S. dollars). Zhou and Bu were
sentenced to prison terms of 15 and 14 years respectively.
</P>
<P>
Liu noted that most smuggling cases are connected with regional
protectionism, and the Supreme Court is looking into this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Council Meeting Approves Two Draft Law Amendments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua)-- The ninth executive meeting of
the State Council which convened here today has examined and
approved in principle the amended draft laws on highways and
military service.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting, presided over by premier Zhu
Rongji, pointed out existing problems in road and vehicle
management, especially in imposing fees on newly built highways.
</P>
<P>
The revised highway law is expected to standardize fund-raising
practices for highway building and maintenance, and reduce the
financial burden placed on people by illegally imposed road tolls.
</P>
<P>
The participants also agreed on the revised military service
law. They held that the amendment is necessary because the current
law, which was enacted in 1984, has some articles that accord
neither with the development of China's new market economy nor the
development of the armed force in the new historic period.
</P>
<P>
The two draft laws will be submitted to the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress for examination and
approval.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education, Top Priority for HKSAR: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) said here
Wednesday that the SAR government must give top priority to
education to take Hong Kong forward in an increasingly competitive
world.
</P>
<P>
In the years 1999-2000, education will continue to be the
single biggest item of recurrent expenditure, Tung said when
delivering his second Policy Address before the Legislative
Council Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the economic downturn, total recurrent spending in
this area will rise to 44 billion HK dollars (5.64 billion U.S.
dollars), Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Tung went on to say that the government will provide over 500
million HK dollars ( 64.10 million U.S. dollars) in grants to
public schools from 1999 to 2003 to help improve their management
and the quality of education.
</P>
<P>
To improve further the quality and professionalism of teachers
in Hong Kong, which are backbone of the education system, the
government will allocate 20 million HK dollars (2.56 million
U.S. dollars) to set up a General Teaching Council, the chief
executive said.
</P>
<P>
The government will also develop an award scheme, which will
recognize high performance and stimulate a culture of quality in
the teaching profession and provide subject training in music
and art and crafts to some 600 teachers annually over the next
seven years to ensure an all-round education for students.
</P>
<P>
The government will work towards the target of providing
primary school students with whole-day schooling from 2007-2008,
Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The government remains fully committed to the promotion of
mother tongue teaching though the government realizes that the
implementation of the mother-tongue learning initiative caused
some concern in the community.
</P>
<P>
Tung explained that the first reason is that expert opinion
world wide is that students learn best in their mother-tongue and
the second reason is that the government is committed to improve
the ability of Hong Kong's students to use both Chinese and
English.
</P>
<P>
To promote further the use of Information Technology (IT) in
education, in the coming year the government will allocate funds
totaling 630 million HK dollars (80.77 million U.S. dollars) in in
a bid to provide more IT training for teachers, enhance the
accessibility of all students to computers, supply technical
back-up to help schools manage their newly acquired IT facilities
and employ some 250 IT coordinators to help public schools develop
and implement their IT-based initiatives.
</P>
<P>
To enhance Hong Kong's status as a regional center for higher
education, the government will further admit non-local students,
Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Starting from the 1999-2000 academic year, the overall quota of
a maximum of 580 first-year, non-local undergraduate students will
include 150 outstanding Mainland students.
</P>
<P>
With the aim of helping Hong Kong's workforce acquire new
skills or upgrade their existing skills, the government will unify
the existing two Technical Colleges and seven Technical Institutes
by the year 2000 to form a single academic and training
institution, the Hong Kong Institute of Vocational Education.
</P>
<P>
The government will grant 500 million HK dollars (64.10 million
U.S. dollars) to the Employees Retaining Board to enable it to
provide more and better courses for the unemployed, the chief
executive said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the government will boost its support networks for
the jobless, in particular the young people, with the aim of
helping them find work more quickly, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Restructure District Organizations: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), here
Wednesday unveiled the government's plan to restructure the SAR's
district organizations.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his second Policy Address before the Legislative
Council Wednesday afternoon, Tung proposed that the existing
Provisional Municipal Councils not be retained after the terms of
office of their members expire at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
A new policy bureau will be set up to coordinate and direct
policy on environmental hygiene, waste management, food safety and
nature conservation, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The new policy bureau will be underpinned by a new Department
of Food and Environmental Hygiene, as well as the existing
Environmental Protection Department and the Agriculture and
Fisheries Department, he said.
</P>
<P>
The responsibilities for food safety and environmental hygiene
currently under the purview of the Urban and Regional Services
Departments, the Department of Health and the Agriculture and
Fisheries Department will be assumed by the new department.
</P>
<P>
"An advisory committee will be established to give advice on
and monitor the government's work in this area, as well as to
allow greater professional participation in formulating policies,"
the chief executive said.
</P>
<P>
Tung added that the government is finalizing the planning for
the new structure, with a view to it being in place before the end
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The government will also develop a new administrative framework
for the delivery of the services of arts and culture and sports ad
 recreation with the Arts Development Council, the Sports
Development Board and other concerned parties before finalizing
the details of the new structure, so that the government can put
this in place before the end of 1999, Tung disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The 18 District Boards (DB) will be maintained as the
government believes that they will still play a vital role in
empowering the community and providing more accountable and
responsive district services, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the government will provide additional funding to the
DBs for improving the local environment, commissioning district
cultural and recreational activities, promoting more community
building programs, enhancing the DBs' role in advising on and
monitoring municipal service delivery and ensuring that the
government is more responsive to DBs' advice, by consulting them
before finalizing district programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Provide Houses for Needy While Stabilizes Prices: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) said here
Wednesday that the government will continue the construction of an
 average of 50,000 public sector flats in the next four years as
promised last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the actual number of flats built annually by the
private sector over the next four years is likely to vary in line
with market demand, and in line with developers' own commercial
consideration, Tung said, when delivering his second Policy
Address before the Legislative Council Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In his maiden Policy Address last year, Tung pledged to produce
85,000 flats annually, with 50,000 provided by the public sector
and 35,000 provided by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
In respect of the public rental component, the government
remains fully committed to ensuring that no household in genuine
need of housing should be denied the right to decent accommodation
 and within a reasonable period of time, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We have pledged to reduce the average waiting time for a
public rental unit to three years by 2005, and we are on target to
 achieve this, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the private residential market, "the first priority
is to do what we can to promote stability in this sector," Tung
said. It is now necessary and desirable for property prices to
stabilize, Tung stressed.
</P>
<P>
Property is one of the most important components of the economy
and a good home is also an important factor in maintaining the
quality of life and the residential property market in particular
serves as both a major vehicle for the personal investment of
wealth and a public barometer of social stability, Tung added.
</P>
<P>
The sharp fall in property prices in the past year has led to a
decrease in asset values and has hit public confidence and if
this trend continues, it will put pressure on the banking system,
Tung noted.
</P>
<P>
"As a government we cannot set the price levels, nor can we
dictate the degree of fluctuation in the market," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"But as the largest single supplier of land in Hong Kong we
undoubtedly have an influence on the long-term pricing of
property," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that the government will decide early in 1999 whether
 or not to lift the nine-month moratorium on land sales up to
March 1999, which the government imposed earlier this year,
having regard to the need to ensure stability in the property
market.
</P>
<P>
"In the long term, the government's focus will be on ensuring
that we produce sufficient land to be able to meet our needs,"
Tung said.
</P>
<P>
A land bank will be created to ensure long term stability of
the property market, Tung said. Turning to the urban renewal
program, the chief executive said that the government would
formulate an Urban Renewal Strategy to provide a comprehensive
framework for urban renewal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
