<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Rules Out Snap Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Wednesday ruled out the possibility of a snap
general election now and said that the Barisan Nasional (BN)
(National Front) government has to focus on reviving the economy.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is not necessary to stretch our limited energy
between managing the economy and the elections," Mahathir, who is
chairman of the ruling 14-party BN coalition, said at the closing
of the National Congress on Economic Recovery here Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
There is no need to hold a general election now because he
believed the majority of Malaysians still supported the BN,
Mahathir said when replying to one congress participant who asked
if the government would call for an early general election to show
the world that the present government still commanded support.
</P>
<P>
A snap general election was much talked about in Malaysia and
speculation is rife about the snap polls taking place in between
November this year and March next year.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "Anyway, holding a general election is a very
big job. You need full attention and managing the economy also
needs full attention."
</P>
<P>
It would be difficult to handle both the election and the
economy at the same time, he said.
</P>
<P>
The BN component parties have also expressed strong support for
the present leadership, Mahathir said, adding "so we (the BN
government) are still strong."
</P>
<P>
He said only if there was to be mass defection by BN component
parties, would the government consider calling for early polls.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia holds a general election every five years and the last
one was held on April 25, 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
