<HEADLINE> German Runner Suspended For Doping Suspicion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- German marathon runner Uta Pippig
has been suspended for abnormally high levels of testosterone,
German Athletics Federation (DLV) officials said on Wednesday in
Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
Pippig, a three-time winner of the Boston Marathon between
1994 and 1996 and the New York Marathon in 1993, had her samples
tested during training in Boulder, the United States, on April 23.
</P>
<P>
Both samples showed abnormally high levels of testosterone, a
performance enhancing hormone, said Klaus Mueller, chief of the
Kreischa lab that examined Pippig's samples.
</P>
<P>
Pippig will be banned for two years if DLV legal committee
rules that Pippig is guilty of doping, said Theo Rous, DLV vice
president and chief anti-doping official.
</P>
<P>
Pippig told the lab she took some medicine to battle a viral
infection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
