<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Shekel Dips to Record-Low Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Under heavy selling pressure,
the Israeli currency shekel tumbled Tuesday to a record low
against the U.S. dollar, prompting fears for the approaching of
"Asian contagion."
</P>
<P>
For the first time in history, the Israeli currency fell below
4.00 shekels against a dollar, a psychological line drawn by many
dealers.
</P>
<P>
The representative rate of Bank of Israel, the central bank,
finished Tuesday at 4.011 shekels to a dollar, and one dollar
bought 4.1 shekels in inter-bank trading.
</P>
<P>
This meant a 2.04 percent devaluation of the shekel.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's trading was characterized by sharp fluctuations and
heavy demand for the dollar. Most of the activity was by foreign
banks trying to cover their positions, as well as by companies and
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
"There are clearly certain parties purchasing foreign currency
and driving the shekel down," Finance Minister Ya'acov Neeman said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
To defend against possible losses, some of the banks went into
a selling spree of the shekel, sending the market crushing.
</P>
<P>
The prominent seller of the shekel was Deutsche Bank. According
to dealers' estimates, it alone sold 100 million and 150 million
dollars worth of shekels Tuesday and last Friday respectively to
fend off losses from its large holdings of shekel-dominated bonds.
</P>
<P>
Other large sellers included Merill Lynch, Bankers Trust and
Citibank.
</P>
<P>
The shekel has lost 13 percent of its value against the dollar
since the beginning of this year and seen a continuing downward
trend on the currency market recently.
</P>
<P>
Local financial analysts said that the negative atmosphere on
international currency markets, rather than anything happening in
Israel, is the main reason for the decline in the shekel.
</P>
<P>
A analyst told the Jerusalem Post newspaper that the financial
crises in Asia and Russia are getting steadily worse and will
rapidly evolve into a global recession.
</P>
<P>
The financial institutions are therefore being forced to reduce
their exposure everywhere, including Israel, and intend to hold
assets with little or no perceived risk, he said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the market is expected to be volatile in the
coming days.
</P>
<P>
In response to the plunge, the country's two leading economic
policy-makers - Neeman and Bank of Israel Governor Jacob Frenkel -
noted Tuesday that the shekel's depreciation was in line with the
law of supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
There was no need for the central bank to intervene, they
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Neeman said that although there are crises in some
parts of the world, Israel is "aware of the situation" and "we
built a wall between us and the storm, and if we act wisely, we
can even exploit the opportunities in the world economy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
