<HEADLINE> Educational Cooperation Between China and Australia Strengthened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Education
Association for International Exchange (CEAIE) signed a higher
education cooperation agreement today with its Australian
counterpart, the Australian Vice-Chancellor's Committee (AV-CC).
</P>
<P>
The agreement, concluded at the Chinese Ministry of Education,
will complement the government-to-government accord on educational
cooperation between the two countries. Under the agreement, the
two nations will cooperate in advancing university teaching,
research, scholarship and management at their member
institutions. The cooperation will involve information sharing,
staff and student exchanges, mutual recognition of qualifications,
staff training, research exchange programs and university
management.
</P>
<P>
The CEAIE is a national non-governmental organization engaged
in international cooperation. Since its establishment 17 years
ago, it has engaged in cooperative activities with nearly 100
foreign educational organizations.
</P>
<P>
The AV-CC is the major organization representing Australian
universities nationally and internationally. Founded in 1920, the
AV-CC acts as an advisor to the government on higher education
issues.
</P>
<P>
China is fast recognizing Australia as a partner in promoting
quality education. It is estimated that between 1997 and 2001
there will be a 39 percent growth in the number of Chinese student
in Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
