<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Grain Markets To Remain Stable After Floods (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The biggest floods since 1954
will not ignite an overall rise of grain prices, and prices will
remain stable at the current level until at least next year, said
today's China Economic Times.
</P>
<P>
The flooding had at least one merit -- it helped halt
the three-year gradual sinking of the massive Chinese grain
market, according to grain expert Xie Yang.
</P>
<P>
"At least until well into next year, grain prices should remain
relatively stable," said Xie. "However, we cannot rule out the
possibility of drastic rises for certain types of grain in this
period."
</P>
<P>
Xie, a researcher with the State Council Development Research
Center, said that the floods, coupled with grain-price structural
adjustment, will cause less than five billion kilos of grain
reduction this year, which means a one percent loss against the
nation's estimated total grain output.
</P>
<P>
He believes that the one percent loss in grain output will
not much influence grain prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has huge grain reserves totalling 200 billion
kilos, compared with an annual domestic need of about 110 billion
kilos.
</P>
<P>
China will enjoy a heavy grain surplus for a long time, and
with the Chinese yuan remaining undevalued, grain prices should
not rise in the next one or two years, said Xie.
</P>
<P>
International grain trade will also help maintain a stable
grain market in China, the researcher noted.
</P>
<P>
He explained that Chinese grain prices are now roughly the same
as international prices, minimizing the effect on China of changes
in the world grain market.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Chinese farmers hold at least 350
billion kilos of grain in their own granaries, which also serves
as a strong guarantor of a stable grain market, said Xie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Build Houses With Local Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Institute of
Architects (NIA) has embarked on a project to build prototype
housing estates with local raw materials as a contribution to the
country's "housing for all" campaign.
</P>
<P>
At the on-going Archi-Build Exhibition held in capital Abuja,
Chairman of the Organizing Committee of the exhibition, Jimoh
Famoraja said that NIA had already acquired land in the Federal
Capital Territory to serve as demonstration center for the
building project.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the NIA would involve various levels of
governments in the country in order to overcome the problem of
land and other logistics, Daily Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Famoraja said that over the years, the NIA had done researches
into and perfected on the technologies for the use of local raw
materials in house building in the most populous African country.
</P>
<P>
The five-day exhibition which started Monday is aimed at
serving as a forum for demonstrating the techniques and promoting
the use of local materials in the construction of housing estates
in the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Famoraja, the price has been fixed at about 4,000
U.S. Dollars for a prototype two-bedroom bungalow in the proposed
estates in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
A study compiled by Nigerian Federal Office of Statistics
shows that more than 50 percent of Nigerians both in the rural
and urban areas live in slums.
</P>
<P>
The just published study indicates that 87.3 percent of urban
Nigerian households with about four to 12 persons live in single
rooms while only a minimal five percent live in flats, 0.5
percent in duplexes and 7.2 percent in whole buildings
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The study describes the general housing conditions of a
majority of Nigerians as very deplorable and the situation has
not changed to date as the slums are springing up, especially in
the urban areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
