<HEADLINE> Reinforced SADC Troops to Secure Northern Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Southern African
Development Community (SADC) military intervention in Lesotho
enters a new and dangerous phase Wednesday when troops began an
attempt to secure the volatile northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
South African media reported that further 750 soldiers will be
deployed in that part of the kingdom, bringing the number of SADC
troops in Lesotho -- from South Africa and Botswana -- to 3,500.
</P>
<P>
Robbie Hartslief, commander of the joint operations,
said that he did not expect to see the troops withdrawn until at
least after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The troops are commissioned to gain control of the area from
the hands of rebel Lesotho soldiers, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Another problem facing Lesotho is that a large number of
weapons had fallen into civilian hands during the uprising in
late September.
</P>
<P>
Hartslief said that many youths were in possession of the
weapons, particularly AK-47 assault rifles, machine guns and
nine-millimeter revolvers.
</P>
<P>
Hartslief and Commander of the Botswana Defense Force
contingent, Gideon Masisi, also revealed that last month's arson
and looting of Maseru was allowed to go on unhindered because the
SADC forces were under strict orders not to act against the
civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
