<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Grain Markets To Remain Stable After Floods (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xie's confidence in a stable grain market also comes from two
figures he personally holds as well-tested grain-price barometers
over his years of observation.
</P>
<P>
One figure is the per capita grain output of 370 kilos. Grain
prices are set to rise when a year's per capita grain output is
less than this figure. Xie estimates that China's per capita grain
output will be above 388 kilos for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The other figure is the yearly fluctuation of grain output of
15 billion kilos. China's summer grain output, indeed, was less
than 15 billion kilos this year, but that resulted mainly from
grain structural adjustment, and the floods played a very minor
role in this reduction. With the autumn harvest expected to be
bumper one, the entire year's grain decrease will be just about
five billion kilos.
</P>
<P>
While allaying the fears of urban residents, Xie is actually
calling for measures to raise grain prices.
</P>
<P>
He said that since August 1995 until this year's floods, grain
prices fell by 38 percent from their peak. For example, rice saw a
price reduction, selling at only three yuan a kilo.
</P>
<P>
Sharp price declines have caused huge losses to grain producers
and distributors and they need some protection, said Xie.
</P>
<P>
Another benefit of a grain price rise will be to activate the
Chinese economy, which has suffered some slowdown this year, he
argues.
</P>
<P>
"A reasonable grain-price rise will help pull up the prices of
other commodities, which will add new vigor to the market," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
