<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CSSHR President Addresses Civil, Political Rights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- China's recent signing of the
International Covenant for Civil and Political Rights represents
the "logical and natural development" of the country's efforts to
realize political democracy over the past century, according to
Zhu Muzhi, president of the Chinese Society for Studies of Human
Rights (CSSHR).
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the move readily shows that China attaches great
importance to human rights, including economic, social, cultural,
and civil and political rights.
</P>
<P>
China's modern history had included struggles for both national
independence and political democracy, and the Chinese citizens
lacked the right to practice political democracy until the
founding of new China in 1949, Zhu recalled.
</P>
<P>
Since then, according to Zhu, the Chinese people have, however,
taken an active part in the nation's construction and in the
establishment and implementation of socialist democracy.
</P>
<P>
He went on to note that the Chinese people now enjoy extensive
an unprecedented human rights, including civil and political
rights.
</P>
<P>
The status of civil and political rights in China can be judged
from many perspectives, with the most important aspect centering
on political democracy, Zhu said, adding that the Chinese people
demand the freedom of speech, publication, assembly and
association, parades and demonstrations, and the rights of
personal freedom and judicial protection, as the means of fully
expressing their opinions and pursuing their interests, especially
in terms of political democracy.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Zhu said, China has been implementing socialist
democracy and adopting the people's congress system in order to
guarantee running things in accordance to the will of the majority
of the people.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy has witnessed rapid sustained growth, with
constant improvings in living standards and an increasingly strong
national strength, he said. The achievements represent the
accomplishment of the demands and will of the Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
The tremendous achievements are directly attributed to the
implementation of the policies and plans outlined by the people's
congresses at all levels, and this shows the people's congress
system in China is a democratic system, and that the Chinese
citizens have the civil rights and political rights to acquire
their freedom of expression and pursue their interests, Zhu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CSSHR President Addresses Civil, Political Rights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's human rights situation is by no means perfect in every
way, and there is still much room for further improvement, Zhu
said. After its signing of the Covenant, the country will strive
to carry forward its achievements and overcome shortcomings in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
There are many areas that still require further improvement,
and the most important thing is to extend socialist democracy and
perfect the legal system and both are closely inter-related, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Zhu went on to explain that the people's congress system should
be further improved at all levels, from the central authorities
down to grassroots levels, to guarantee representing fully the
popular feelings of the Chinese people. He added that a legal
system to safeguard socialist democracy must be perfected to as to
ensure that the country will be run according to law and a new
socialist legal system with Chinese characteristics be built in
the future.
</P>
<P>
Some 328 laws and related codes, more than 700 administrative
regulations and 5,000-plus local rules have been drafted since
China introduced the reform and opening-up policies 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zhu underlined the special significance of giving
full play to China's democratic tradition in implementing the mass
line. Any policy--making process must be first of all based on the
extensive solicitation of opinions of the masses and, when policy
decisions are reached, they must be subjected to be tested by the
masses of people in the course of practice.
</P>
<P>
As a research organization, Zhu said, the CSSHR will, as
always, continue to promote civil and political rights in China,
and will actively spread the related knowledge on the civil rights
and political rights as well as the correct understanding in this
regard amongst the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, since China did not participate in drafting the
Covenant and its national conditions differ from that in other
countries, the Chinese government will pay special attention to
the issue as properly adapting the Covenant to the existing
situation, and the country's existing laws and regulations, Zhu
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
