<HEADLINE> Abnormal Behavior of Fish Baffles Experts in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Fishes in the Bay of Bengal are
behaving strangely for the past four months and of late dead fish
are found floating the sea, baffling fisheries experts who fear
that some serious changes have taken place in their living
environment.
</P>
<P>
An abnormal movement of big-sized fish from the sea towards the
shallow waters near the coastline is constantly reported.
</P>
<P>
In an extreme case, a big colony of hilsa fish was found coming
to the mouth of the river Naaf, at a depth of only three meters of
water, on the Bangladesh-Myanmar border, The Independent daily
Wednesday quoted a senior official of the Department of Fisheries
(DF) as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The abundance of big fish in the market during the current
season was due to the desperate movement of the fish for food and
hospitable environment," an expert hypothesized, saying "This is
not a good sign because this indicates that the parent fish got
trapped in large numbers this year."
</P>
<P>
The living environment of fishes in the deep waters might have
changed due to a change in the water temperature, or dumping of
toxic wastes by foreign ships, another expert guessed.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries expert say that the huge catch of hilsa, laitya and
other big fish recorded throughout the coastal belt during the
past few months might be the result of this abnormal behavior of
the fishes.
</P>
<P>
Neither the DF nor the Fisheries Research Institute have done
an independent study of the problem, and they have only gathered a
picture by observing the trend in fish catch this season and
listening to conversations of fishermen, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries Ministry officials are under the impression that
fishes had ran towards the coast due to an earthquake that had
shaken the deep seas near the Andaman and Nicobar Islands during
the first fortnight of August, the report stated.
</P>
<P>
An expert on marine fishery who works with the DF, however,
ruled out fishes being driven towards the shallow waters by an
under-water quake.
</P>
<P>
His impression was that there might have been some changes in
the environment in the deep sea due to a rise in the water
temperature caused by El-Nino that had been very vigorous until
the end of May.
</P>
<P>
The temperature change kills the plankton that grow in water
and are taken by fishes as food, he said, adding that absence or
scarcity of food might have forced the fishes to rush towards the
shallow waters for food.
</P>
<P>
He did not rule out the dumping of toxic wastes in the Bay by
foreign ships.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of the Ministry of Fisheries and Live-stock,
and of the DF Tuesday started investigating the extent of the
problem, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Marine fish account for over 21 percent of the nearly 1.4
million tons of fish consumed in Bangladesh annually, official
figures show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
