<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Up 2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Strong gains on the Japanese
market lifted the Australian share market by almost two percent
Wednesday, with blue chips leading the way.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed up 49 points, or 1.97 percent,
at 2,540.2, off a high of 2,543.5 and a low of 2,490.8.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei 225 Index surged 804 points, or 6.2 percent, to
13,826.0 after investors welcomed Japanese government policies to
spur its crumbling economy and rescue its banks.
</P>
<P>
Paul Xiradis, equities director at funds manager AUSBIL
Partners, said that the gains in Japan might not be sustained as
on previous occasions after government prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
"It's difficult to be totally convinced that there is a turning
point at this part of the junction, but certainly it is very
encouraging," he said of Japanese developments.
</P>
<P>
On the stock market, the all industrials index added 82.9
points at 4,421.8 and the all resources index closed up 22.4
points, or 2.22 percent, at 1,030.5.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 292.54 million shares traded valued at
630 million U.S. dollars, with 604 rises, 469 falls and 356 stocks
steady.
</P>
<P>
Optimism that Japan has broken the political impasse on the
recapitalization of its failed banks, easing some fears of a world
credit-lending squeeze, pushed local bank and resource stocks
higher as Japan is a major market for Australian commodities.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank gained 71 cents, or 3.71 percent,
to 19.85 Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia gained
78 cents, or 4.21 percent, to 19.30 Australian dollars, ANZ bank
gained 14 cents to 8.72 Australian dollars, and Westpac bank rose
eight cents to 8.88 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP, whose share price had recently slumped on
concerns that the Japanese recession would reduce worldwide demand
for its products, climbed 46.1 cents, or 3.85 percent, to 12.441
Australian dollars. Global miner Rio Tinto rose 14.8 cents to
19.39 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 9.5 points, or 0.79 percent, higher at
1,223.0, off a low of 1,201.0.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion closed 1.80 U.S. dollars higher at 298.05 U.S.
dollars an ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
