<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes 2 U.S. Cents Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed at
its highest level in two months Wednesday, around two U.S. cents
stronger, when a surge in buying lifted the currency through the
60.00 U.S. cents level in afternoon trade.
</P>
<P>
Nick Volanakis, senior foreign exchange dealer at Colonial
State Bank, said market perception that the local currency was
grossly undervalued led to a flurry of aggressive buying.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed Wednesday at 60.58 U.S. cents, up
from Tuesday's close of 58.55 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
It last closed over the 60.00 U.S. cents level on August 7,
when it ended at 60.15 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
A report by investment bank Goldman Sachs also helped boost the
currency Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Goldman Sachs, in its weekly report, said the Australian dollar
would see 62.00 U.S. cents before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The report also said the Australian dollar was trading 27
percent below its fair value, and would rebound early next year.
</P>
<P>
Another factor that proved positive for the local dollar was a
rebound in the Japanese stock market, which contributed to a
strong rise on the Australian share market Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was buying 77.97 Japanese yen from 77.80
yen, and 0.9865 German marks from 0.9530 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
