<HEADLINE> Indian Scientists Find Ways to Make High-Quality Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian scientists have found
ways to make high-quality paper.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the National Chemical Laboratory (NCL) in Pune
about 1,500 km southwest of New Delhi have patented a process to
isolate a fungus that can enhance paper quality as well as reduce
the use of toxic chemicals in paper industry, Press Trust of India
(PTI) said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The cephalosporium strain, which is isolated in NCL, is the
first fungal strain to show selective enzyme action on pulp which
will help produce superior rayon-grade paper, PTI quoted scientist
M. C. Srinivasan as saying.
</P>
<P>
Plants contain carbohydrates in the form of cellulose and
hemicellulose. To produce good-quality pulp, scientists are on the
lookout for strains that contain xylanase enzyme which selectively
degrades the undesirable hemicellulose component but is free of
cellulose enzyme that breaks down cellulose. Cellulose primarily
determines paper quality. NCL's new strain was found to
selectively degrade hemicellulose. It, however, does not affect
cellulose, Srinivasan said.
</P>
<P>
Besides its cellulose-free xylanase activity, the enzyme was
found to be stable under highly alkaline conditions, which is
another desirable attribute as pulp processing takes place at high
temperature and under alkaline conditions.
</P>
<P>
As fungal action enhances pulp brightness, its use will reduce
the amount of cancer-causing chlorine compounds needed to bleach
pulp, Srinivasan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
