<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Appoints Council of International Advisers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) has appointed
a Council of International Advisers to advise him on strategic
issues pertinent to the long-term development of Hong Kong from an
international perspective.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by the SAR Government Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The council, chaired by Tung, comprises distinguished
international business and corporate leaders. Its members include
business leaders from Siemens AG, Royal Philips Electronics, Power
 Corporation of Canada, Motorola Inc., American International
Group, Inc., Deutsche Bank AG, Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux, The News
Corporation Limited, HSBC Holdings, The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi,
Ltd., Toyota Motor Corporation, Royal Dutch/Shell Group of
Companies, Federal Reserve Bank of United States of America, and
General Electric Company.
</P>
<P>
The administrative secretary, financial secretary, secretary
for trade and industry and head of the Central Policy Unit of the
SAR Government are also members.
</P>
<P>
The Council is expected to meet at least once a year and will
hold its first meeting in January 1999, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
Expressing appreciation for the members' participation in the
council, Tung said he believes the Council will benefit from the
expertise of and advice from these prominent members of the
international business community.
</P>
<P>
"They will be best placed to advise, from an international
perspective, on the global and regional development trends
affecting Hong Kong's long-term development and the perception of
the international business community on Hong Kong's plans and
programs of activities.
</P>
<P>
"They will also be able to advise on such matters as the
investments Hong Kong would need to make in order to enhance our
role as a world-class commercial and financial center, and as a
dynamic Special Administrative Region of China under the concept
of 'one country, two systems'," Tung said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
