<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Sets Up Surveillance Mechanism Against Financial Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) is putting in place an informal surveillance
mechanism to guard against future financial crises similar to the
ongoing one in Asia, ASEAN deputy secretary-general Suthad
Setboonsarng said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Suthad, attending a two-day ASEAN economic minister meeting
here, said at a press conference that ASEAN finance ministers
agreed on Sunday in Washington on the "informal system" involving
all nine ASEAN member countries.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers pledged to provide on a regular basis
certain economic data which include macro-economic indicators and
figures related to trade and fiscal balance, and interest rate and
exchange rate policies, Suthad said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the mechanism will work through "peer review" to
dissuade member governments from pursuing certain policies that
could harm the entire region.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta-based ASEAN Secretariat will also set up an "ASEAN
surveillance technical support unit" that works with experts from
the
Manila-based Asian Development Bank in collecting and monitoring
the data, Suthad said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that submission of the data is not "mandatory" and
that each country would have to trust fellow members.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism would "provide an early warning system" and
provide a forum to monitor and discuss economic developments"
which have a bearing on the well-being of ASEAN members, Suthad
said.
</P>
<P>
He said ASEAN finance ministers will meet twice a year,
starting next March in Hanoi, Vietnam, to analyze the data and
provide recommendations.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN consists of Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Rates in Singapore </HEADLINE>
