<HEADLINE> Mainland To Play Pivotal Role for HK Economic Recovery: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
said Wednesday in his 1998 policy address that Hong Kong must
strengthen cooperation with the mainland in order to bring its
battered economy back to the path of growth.
</P>
<P>
In his second policy address unveiled Wednesday, Tung said that
Hong Kong needs to adopt two key initiatives to stimulate its
economy, which is predicted to shrink four percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"First, we must work to maintain Hong Kong's status as an
international trade center. Second, we must strengthen our
cooperation with the mainland in all areas," the chief executive
told the 60-member Legislature.
</P>
<P>
He said that China's interior has historically provided the
impetus for Hong Kong's economic growth, and Hong Kong has always
played an important role in promoting the mainland relationship
with other countries. Over the past two decades, Hong Kong has
become the mainland's most important center for fund-raising,
trading and re-export.
</P>
<P>
As the World Bank predicted, China will become one of the
largest economic entities in the world in the 21st century, which,
 Tung noted, indicates that Hong Kong will have different roles to
 play and new functions to perform.
</P>
<P>
"We must now consider how to reinforce our role as the bridge
between China and the international community, as well as how to
enhance our function as a leading business center for China and
the Asia Pacific region," said the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the Special Administrative Region (SAR)
government will play a leading role in creating an environment
conducive to closer cooperation between the mainland and Hong
Kong, ranging from expanding economic links to enhancing academic
exchange.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation will put Hong Kong back on course for a
prosperous future, by offering businesses greater scope for
development and people more job opportunities, said Tung. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
