<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tung Unveils New Policy for Hong Kong's Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
unveiled the 1998 Policy Address here Wednesday, which put forth
strategies to ride Hong Kong out of the current economic
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Tung Wednesday presented to the 60-member Legislature his
second policy address, entitled "From Adversity to Opportunity."
He laid out key strategies for growth, namely, to broaden Hong
Kong's economic horizon by developing high-value-added industries,
and to reinforce existing strengths of Hong Kong as an
international financial and trade center.
</P>
<P>
Tung acknowledged that the Asia financial turmoil has not only
rocked Hong Kong's economy, which is predicted to contract about
four percent this year, but also exposed inherent weakness in its
economic structure.
</P>
<P>
To bring the battered economy back to the path of growth, Hong
Kong needs to rely on the new engines, innovation and technology,
said the Chief Executive, who proposed in his speech to set up an
Applied Science and Technology Research Institute, and inject five
 billion HK dollars (640 million U.S. dollars) to launch an
Innovation and Technology Fund.
</P>
<P>
He enumerated a string of government initiatives in promoting
technology-driven industries, including:
</P>
<P>
* positioning Hong Kong as an Internet hub and information
technology center in the Asia Pacific region,
</P>
<P>
* launching an on-line government electronic services network,
</P>
<P>
* building a world class teleport to provide the best possible
global satellite links,
</P>
<P>
* Setting up a 100-million-HK dollar (12.8 million U.S. dollar)
film development fund to rejuvenate local film industry, which has
a promising large market, and
</P>
<P>
* taking forward proposals to turn Hong Kong into the
international center for Chinese medicine.
</P>
<P>
Apart from expanding economic horizon, Tung suggested that Hong
Kong continue to build on its existing strengths to ensure the
long-term economic vitality. In the wake of the currency crisis,
Hong Kong will enhance its role as an international financial
services center by boosting regulatory system and developing new
products, such as a venture board for the trade of shares in
smaller and emerging companies.
</P>
<P>
In his policy address, Tung also listed specific measures to
stimulate the flagging tourism industry, facilitate small and
medium-sized enterprises, build large infrastructure projects, and
stabilize property prices.
</P>
<P>
Education is a top priority despite the economic downturn, Tung
told the 60-member Legislative Council. In 1999-2000, education
will continue to be the single biggest item of recurrent
expenditure, amounting to 44 billion HK dollars (5.6 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government plans to grant 500 million HK dollars (64
million U.S. dollars) for retraining employees, in an effort to
ease the worsening unemployment, which hit a decade high of five
percent.
</P>
<P>
In his policy address, Tung also pledged to create a better
environment, taking care of people in need, and improve health and
public hygiene.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive stressed time and again in his two-hour
speech that Hong Kong must strengthen cooperation with the
mainland in all areas for an earlier economic recovery and
sustained long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
"We must now consider how to reinforce our role as the bridge
between China and the international community, as well as how to
enhance our function as a leading business center for China and
the Asia Pacific region," he told the legislators.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, Tung said that the recovery of the Hong Kong
economy hinges on four factors: an improvement in the external
economic environment, a steady interest rate, stability in the
property market, and the restoration of public confidence.
</P>
<P>
He called on Hong Kong people not to lose confidence, which is
 the most crucial factor for recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
