<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technology to Become New Engine for HK's Growth: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
pledged to make innovation and technology Hong Kong's new engines
of economic growth in his 1998 policy address, which was unveiled
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Innovation and technology are important drivers of economic
growth," Tung stated in his second policy address at the
Legislative Council on Wednesday afternoon. "In a knowledge-based
global economy, they are essential in adding value, increasing
productivity and enhancing our overall competitiveness," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive proposed to set up an Applied Science and
Technology Research Institute, which, now a dearth to Hong Kong,
will serve as a mid-stream link between basic scientific research
and its commercial application in the future.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government will inject five billion HK dollars
(640 million U.S. dollars) to launch an Innovation and Technology
Fund.
</P>
<P>
The two initiatives were part of the recommendation package
submitted in September by the Commission on Innovation and
Technology, which, founded in March this year, was charged with
the task of advising the Chief Executive on technology and
industry policies.
</P>
<P>
Tung vowed in his policy address to build Hong Kong into an
Internet hub and information technology center in the Asia Pacific
region. Accordingly, Hong Kong will develop a world class teleport
to provide the best possible global satellite links and launch an
on-line government electronic services network before 2,000.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive planned to earmark 100 million HK dollars
(12.8 million U.S. dollars) to rejuvenate local film industry,
which has a potential audience of over one billion in the
world-wide Chinese community. The fund will be used to promote
creativity and application of technology in film production.
</P>
<P>
Chinese medicine is another potential competitive edge Hong
Kong could exploit in the future, said the Chief Executive, who
promised to take forward proposals aimed at turning Hong Kong into
 an international center for Chinese medicine and medical
practitioners.
</P>
<P>
Drawing a lesson from the Asian financial turmoil, which has
already dragged Hong Kong into a painful period of economic
readjustment, Tung said that Hong Kong's economic base has been
too narrow and the new strategies for growth will be to focus on
expanding diversity of the economy.
</P>
<P>
High value-added industries are a key focus of development in
the wake of the regional financial turbulence, said Tung. "A clear
policy objective is to enhance the capability of Hong Kong firms
to innovate, stimulate technological development, and encourage
its commercialization and application in Hong Kong," he told the
legislators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
