<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Absenteeism by American Workers at All-time High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Unscheduled absenteeism by
American workers is at an all-time high and small businesses are
hit the hardest, a new human resources survey suggested.
</P>
<P>
As shown by the annual survey on absenteeism, released this
week by CCH Inc., the absences are now costing small business
owners nearly twice as much as they did four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The yearly absenteeism rate for small businesses has soared 46
percent since 1994, from 5.4 missed days per employee to eight
days in 1998, said CCH in the survey report.
</P>
<P>
The survey, the only of its kind in the United States, covered
400 U.S. companies, with a total of 800,000 employees. And CCH
Inc. is a leading provider of business and tax information.
</P>
<P>
While many innovative employment benefit programs are viewed as
effective in stemming the tide, CCH said, few of the programs are
actually in place and entrepreneurs expect absenteeism to get even
worse.
</P>
<P>
Absenteeism means unscheduled time off for any reason, such as
for family issues, personal illnesses, personal needs, entitlement
mentality and stress.
</P>
<P>
As the rate of absenteeism for small business soars, so does
the cost. CCH figures that unscheduled absences could cost small
business 1,044 U.S. dollars per employee this year, or 38 percent
more than the 757-dollar average for all businesses. That puts the
possible total price tag of these absences for a small business
with 99 employees as high as 103,000 dollars per year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there are indirect costs associated with unscheduled
absences, including overtime pay for other employees, hiring a
temporary employees and supervisory time spent rearranging work
schedules.
</P>
<P>
A decline in morale and lower productivity among workers who
are expected to cover for an absent employee may also add to
indirect costs. These hidden costs can add another 15 to 25
percent to the direct cost, CCH said.
</P>
<P>
Experts say one of the best ways to control unscheduled
absences is to provide employees with paid time off, a bank of
hours to be used for various purposes rather than separate
accounts for vacation, sick leave or personal time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
