<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidential Adviser on Petroleum Appointed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar has appointed Aret Adams, former managing
director of the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation, as his
special adviser on petroleum resources.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Tuesday night in capital Abuja by the Chief
Press Secretary's office also announced other six appointments
which immediately took effect, local press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Petroleum Resources Ministry was scrapped when
the federal cabinet was reshuffled in August this year.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar had indicated that the Petroleum Resources Ministry
would be brought under his supervision as part of measures to
combat the lingering fuel crisis in the oil-exporting country.
</P>
<P>
The decision to bring the ministry under the presidency
followed the fuel crisis in the industry resulting in the
breakdown of most of the nation's refineries.
</P>
<P>
The newly-appointed special adviser is an ardent believer in
the complete overhaul of the petroleum industry and one of the
proponents of divestment of government's interest in the oil
sector.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with This Day newspaper, Adams said that
"I have a very strong reason that we should privatize the
refineries and privatize any public sector organization that is
supposed to deliver results in a profit basis."
</P>
<P>
The adviser also believes in the immediate deregulation of the
downstream sector of the petroleum industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
