<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices skyrocketed in Tokyo
Wednesday with the Nikkei index posting this year's second-biggest
point gain on expectations that a new bank-recapitalization bill
will be enacted during the ongoing Diet, or parliament, session.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 803.97 points, or 6.17
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 13,825.61.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all First Section
issues, surged 50.03 points or 5.02 percent to 1,046.98.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section was heavy at an estimated 620
million shares, up from Tuesday's 401.22 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Shares were higher across the board, with the banking sector
rebounding 8.69 percent as investors' confidence in the financial
system apparently improved because of possible approval of the
bank-recapitalization bill, which would allow the government to
inject public funds into capital-short banks, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Other than the progress of the bank legislation, traders
attributed the climb to growing expectation that the European
countries will soon implement joint interest rate cuts to prevent
their economies from falling into recession.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,337 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
overwhelmed losers 1,067 to 127, while 102 issues ended
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
