<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Upholds Right to Use Force against Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said Wednesday that Iran would not give up the right to
use force against the Afghan Taliban militia for the killing of
nine Iranian diplomats and reporter.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that before the use of force, the Taliban would submit
to the demands of the international community and Iran" to punish
the killers, return the bodies of other three slain Iranians, and
release all captured Iranians, Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference here that Iran hoped to solve the
issue through diplomatic means and welcomed the visit to the
region of Lakhdar Brahimi, the special envoy of the U.N. Secretary
General on Afghan affairs.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi arrived here Sunday in an effort to defuse the tension
between Iran and the Taliban triggered by the killing of Iranian
diplomats and reporter in northern Afghanistan in August.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Iran waits to see if the Taliban would be brought
to the terms of the international community.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have returned the bodies of six Iranian diplomats
and reporter, but the whereabouts of the bodies of the three
others were still unknown.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, over 30 Iranian drivers and aid
workers, accused of shipping supplies to the opposition forces,
are still held in the Taliban's prisons.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Brahimi's visit was not the only effort by the
international community, but it was the most important one and
Iran hopes the visit would be successful.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent withdrawal of a group of Iranian
diplomats from Pakistan, Kharrazi reiterated that they were
recalled because of the insecure situation there.
</P>
<P>
Iran, predominated by Shiite Muslims, said its diplomats faced
serious terrorist threats in Pakistan, which has an overwhelming
Sunni Muslim population. Their relations tumbled because Islamabad
supported the Taliban and Tehran backed its rival, the Northern
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
However, Kharrazi said Iran hopes its move would not be seen as
a sign of any change in bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
