<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Go to U.S. Court for Refund of F-16s Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has finally decided
to go to U.S. court for the refund of 658 million U.S. dollars
which it paid the United States for the purchase of 28 F-16
fighter planes.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Karachi-based major English daily
Dawn, the Pakistani government has engaged a U.S. law firm, Patton
Boggs, for initiating legal proceedings against the U.S.
government for the breach of contract and recovery of the paid
money.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Law Minister Khalid Anwer is reported to have had
meetings with six U.S. law firms in July this year. And Patton
Boggs has finally been selected after evaluating the proposals of
the U.S. firms, their assessment of the legal aspects and fees.
</P>
<P>
A representative of Patton Boggs will arrive in Pakistan later
this month for the legal matter.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan signed a contract for the purchase of 28 F-16 fighters
on September 27, 1989 at the cost of 1.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In October 1990, the U.S. passed the Pressler amendment which
banned arms supply to Pakistan. Pakistan continued quarterly
payments in the hope that sanctions against it would be lifted.
Pakistan stopped its payment when the U.S. refused to deliver the
planes.
</P>
<P>
The suit for the refund of money would be filed in a U.S. court
of claims. The decision of the court can be impugned in the
relevant circuit of U.S. court of appeals and eventually in the
U.S. supreme court.
</P>
<P>
According to the assessment given to the Pakistani government,
the decision of the court of claims will take about two years. If
any party approached the appellate court, it will take another two
or three years.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government had expected that after Pakistan's
nuclear detonations in May this year, the dispute would be
resolved out of court.
</P>
<P>
However, after a recent visit by Pakistani officials to the
U.S., the government has come to the conclusion that legal remedy
was the only solution of the F-16 issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
