<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Arafat Meet in Three-Way Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EREZ BORDER CROSSING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- During her second
day of shuttle diplomacy Wednesday, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright brought Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser
Arafat together for talks.
</P>
<P>
The trilateral talks, which have just started, took place at
this border crossing between Israel and the Gaza Strip. Netanyahu
and Arafat met here almost exactly a year ago - on October 8 last
year, seven months after the peace process began to falter.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the holding of the trilateral talks itself
signifies that progress has been made in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said Tuesday night
that real progress has been made in the talks and "the mood is
right." But he stressed that dozens of unresolved issues still
remained, such as interim matters, the third redeployment, and
perhaps most importantly, security.
</P>
<P>
Albright is on a mission to bring the two sides closer to
completing a deal for a further Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank, paving the way for a Middle East summit expected to be held
in Washington in mid-October between Netanyahu, Arafat and
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
She has held two rounds of talks with Netanyahu and one with
Arafat Tuesday, which she described as "useful." 
</P>
</TEXT>
