<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Lure Foreign Capital to Hi-Tech Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus aims to develop a viable
hi-tech industry amid encouraging signs that major multinationals
abroad may be interested in investing in the area of technology
and energy.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Minister of Commerce and Industry Nicos Rolandis made
the statement in an interview with the weekly business newspaper
"Financial Mirror," published here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rolandis, who just returned from a trip to the United States,
said that following intensive contacts with ranking officials of
major corporations, he felt they have "a lot of interest" in
setting up new divisions that will help toward the creation of a
viable hi-tech industry in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said the immediate areas of interest include software
development, biotechnology, development of new technologies and
energy and design of electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two committees he appointed to hammer out a
new industrial policy, with special emphasis on the creation of a
hi-tech sector, are to hand in their reports by the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
Rolandis said his ministry will also come up with specific
measures to attract foreign investors and set up a mechanism by
which to overcome bureaucratic hurdles confronting foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
On incentives that may be offered to foreign investors,
Rolandis said these include tax breaks, subsidies on the
construction of new production facilities, stable labour costs,
the availability of well-trained staff and other support measures.
</P>
<P>
Moreover he said plans are underway to attract a large number
of Cypriots currently living abroad, who together with the
existing human resources available on the island would become the
nucleus around which a viable hi-tech industry can take shape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
