<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Establishes Special Silk Storehouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- China has recently opened a
special silk storehouse in the city of Wujiang in eastern Jiangsu
Province, in a bid to regulate the prices of silk and products at
the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's largest silk exporting country and the
silk export has been a major source of foreign exchange income.
</P>
<P>
However, the country's silk industry has suffered a decline
since 1994 when uncontrolled competition led to sharp price cuts,
increased stocks and poor economic returns for silk export
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, the government has established a silk
storage system and set up a special storehouse. The government has
decided to allocate two billion yuan (about 240 million
U.S. dollars) to purchase silk in order to regulate the market
price and avoid abnormal fluctuations in both silk production and
prices.
</P>
<P>
Located at the center of China's major silk producing areas,
Wujiang has been one of the country's important bases of silk
production and export. The existing facilities and management
expertise there are favorable for the establishment of the special
silk storehouse.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
