<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangkok's Office Market Expected to Worsen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangkok's office market is
expected to worsen and vacancy rates will range between 35-40
percent in the second half of this year, Thai News Agency (TNA)
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the end of April, the average vacancy rate of offices in
Bangkok's central business district stood at 22 percent, twice of
that in Kuala Lumpur (11 percent) and over four times as much as
that of Manila (4 percent), TNA quoted real estate consultant
Jones Lang Wootton as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vacancies in Bangkok, Jakarta, Kuala Lumpur and Manila are
increasing as new projects are introduced at a time of declining
demand. Manila, Kuala Lumpur and Jakarta will all have vacancy
rates of around 20 percent by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Vacancies in Bangkok will remain some way ahead, with the
completion of new office projects over the second half of this
year, resulting in a vacancy rate of 35-40 percent.
</P>
<P>
By the end of April, office rents in Bangkok were considered as
the cheapest when compared with Manila, Kuala Lumpur and Jakarta.
Rents in Bangkok were expected to fall further in the second half
of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MasterCard Warns of Prejudice Against Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 7 (Xinhua) -- MasterCard International, in an
attempt to ease worries about the financial credibility in
Southeast Asia, has said that its cards issued in the region have
the same credibility as in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The assurance followed press reports that merchants worldwide
refused to accept MasterCard payment cards issued in
crisis-stricken Thailand, Indonesia and Malaysia, Thai News Agency
(TNA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
All Master cards issued in the three countries should be
accepted by merchants worldwide, MasterCard International said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
"During these difficult times, merchants must be reminded that
it is their responsibility to accept MasterCard payments cards
without prejudice," Donald Van Stone, MasterCard International
Southeast Asia's senior vice president and general manager, said
in the statement.
</P>
<P>
MasterCard would guarantee settlement payments for transactions
among its member financial institutions, the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
