<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Amid stormy trading on the currency markets, the shekel
depreciated by 2.04 percent against the dollar Tuesday, with the
representative rate set at a new high of 4.011 shekels to a
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Bank Leumi dealing room head Haim Formowitz said that the main
reason for shekel's decline was the rise of the dollar abroad. He
also said that the currency markets are expected to be volatile in
the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Tuesday that
he would go ahead with construction in Tel Rumeida, a Jewish
enclave in the West Bank city of Hebron, but that the work would
not begin until an archaeological salvage dig has been conducted.
</P>
<P>
With the announcement, Netanyahu apparently tried to please
both settlers pressing for a quick start of construction and
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who has demanded a
halt to settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- A three-way meeting among U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority Chairman
Yasser Arafat will be held Wednesday at the Eretz border crossing
between Israel and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is aimed at bringing Israel and the Palestinians
closer to completing a deal for an Israeli troop withdrawal from
the West Bank. If Albright succeeds in bridging the remaining gaps
over a U.S. peace initiative, a deal may be signed in Washington
later this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
