<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Emerges as New Turpan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Dynasty Winery Co. Ltd.
never dreamed an ideal grape production base would emerge right at
its doorsteps in Chadian Village in the north China municipality
of Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The rather obscure village was home to only a few small
vineyards a short 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
A vineyard filled with heavily laden vines currently stretches
for miles over 1,800 hectares. The vineyard is five times larger
than the famous 1,500-meter Turpan grape corridor in west China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region. The Tianjin vineyard has
estimated annual grape production capacity of some 35,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Tianjin is quite different that in Turpan, a
city widely known as one of the nation's major fruit production
bases. Tianjin grapes are used solely for winemaking, particularly
the Rose Aroma variety which has two national medals for high
quality.
</P>
<P>
The vineyard is a major supplier for the Dynasty Winery, a
Sino-French joint venture which is a flagship enterprise in the
country's wine industry.
</P>
<P>
The winery, however, is not the sole beneficiary, with
statistics show that the vineyard contribute over 100 million
yuan annually in local revenue and grape growers themselves earn
an average 12,000 yuan per year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
