<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hi-tech Ritual Atop Ancient Observatory (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Modern electronic networking
instantly linked China with faraway Britain today atop Beijing's
Ancient Observatory, an epitomizing relic of China's past
scientific glory.
</P>
<P>
Visiting British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Chinese
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing each pressed a computer mouse and on a
wide screen two markers, one reading "To China" and the other "To
Britain," flicked, linking the China Education Research Network
with the British Joint Academic Network.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Blair told a ceremony marking the link-up that
Britain and China have already formed a solid foundation for
scientific, technological and educational cooperation, and that
the two linked institutions have already agreed to more than 700
partnerships. As two countries with long histories and rich
cultural heritages, today's ceremony highlights the enhanced ties
between the two nations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He announced on behalf of the the British government that the
British Science and Technology Office is planning to add 300,000
pounds sterling to bilateral education and scientific
cooperation. The prime minister said he was also delighted to
learn that that Chinese Science and Technology Ministry has
approved matching funds for this cooperative undertaking.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said he considers British Prime
Minister Blair's China visit "an important one" in bilateral ties
and that it will go down in the annals of Sino-British relations
for its significance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
