<HEADLINE> US Urged To Lift Injunction on Timber Imports from NZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Minister for
International Trade Lockwood Smith Wednesday urged the United
States to lift an injunction stopping the issue of new permits or
the renewal or amendment of existing permits for the import of
non-tropical timber from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an on-going annual conference of the New Zealand
Forest Owners Association in Wellington, Smith said New Zealand's
view is that "there is no justification for the injunction", which
was issued by the U.S. District Court in San Francisco in July.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a study of pest intercepts in the U.S. between
August 1995 and March 1998 shows no intercepts on logs and lumber
from New Zealand. "Our view is shared by the U.S. Animal and Plant
Health Inspection Service, an agency of the U.S. Department of
Agriculture," he added.
</P>
<P>
Smith said New Zealand is expecting a hearing to be held in
early January 1999.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Smith said the past year had been a "tough" one
for New Zealand forest industry with exports to Japan and the
Republic of Korea reducing more than a quarter.
</P>
<P>
In those two markets alone, he said, New Zealand has lost
nearly 300 million New Zealand dollars (150 million U.S. dollars)
in export receipts.
</P>
<P>
"Across the board the decline has been 6 percent in the year to
June -- not good, but not totally disastrous as some would have us
believe," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
