<HEADLINE> NZ Should Think About Single Currency with Australia: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A single currency could
replace the
New Zealand and Australian dollars sometime next decade, according
to a
New Zealand banking expert.
</P>
<P>
A Wellington-based newspaper Wednesday frontpaged an interview
with
Professor David Tripe, director of Massey University's Center for
Banking
Studies, quoting him as saying less than three months before the
European
Union takes its first concrete step to a single currency, the
"Euro", New
Zealand "should think about a single currency with Australia --
perhaps
the 'anzac'."
</P>
<P>
Now was the time to start thinking about a single currency,
though it
could take five to 10 years to introduce, he told the Dominion.
</P>
<P>
Tripe noted that a single currency would simplify trade, reduce

business transaction costs and be a further step toward a single
market
building on the Closer Economic Relations agreement between the
two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"We should look at what is going on in Europe carefully because
 there
may be lessons in it which may be of use to us," the professor
said.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand and Australia have had a common currency before --
the
pound sterling. Separate currencies were established after both
countries
set up their own central banks but they moved away from sterling
in value
only after the second World War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
