<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sees Crime Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand saw a 3.5-percent

reduction in reported crime in the year to June 30, according to
Wednesday's The Dominion.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted an official report as
saying
the big reductions in violent and sexual offenses were main
attributers to the achievement.
</P>
<P>
The official report showed that 465,384 offenses were reported
in
the year, a 3.5-percent fall from a year ago. Homicides, including

murder, attempted murder and manslaughter, dropped 27 percent to
116
and sexual offenses 7.4 percent to 3,221.
</P>
<P>
The year also saw a 29.7-percent increase in kidnappings and
abductions and a 9-percent rise in cannabis offenses.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington district led the way with a 9.1-percent
reduction
in crime.
</P>
<P>
Wellington figures for the past year showed nine homicides,
down
from 18 the year before; 7,470 burglaries, down 8.9 percent; and
103
sexual offenses, down 24 percent. But the district also saw an 18-
percent increase in robberies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
