<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lover's Promenade Disappears in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai media once carried
numerous stories about the so-called "Lover's Promenade" along the
famous Bund, a popular attraction for visitors from throughout the
world.
</P>
<P>
However, an Australian tourist recently expressed
disappointment that the formerly popular area has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The Lover's Promenade was popular for over 20 years until
numerous public entertainment venues for young people opened in
the city, according to a local resident name Xu, who lives on
Ermei Street near the Bund.
</P>
<P>
Numerous older Shanghainese met their future mates along the
Bund. Xu, 50, recalled how he referred to the Bund as "the same
old place" when making a date with his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Xunzheng, an academician with the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, said that young couples dating 20 years ago found it
difficult to have a romantic place to spend their leisure time in
the densely populated city of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that couples would congregate along the Lover's
Promenade in droves when the area was at its peak. He said couples
would flock to the area along the Huangpu River levee like birds
at dusk, with little room left for those arriving late.
</P>
<P>
The promenade began to loose its appeal in the mid-1980s when
reform and opening gave the city a new look.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has constructed housing complexes covering two million
sq.m. and modern transportation facilities such as subway and
viaducts in the area over the past two decades. Housing conditions
have improved dramatically and younger Shanghainese now enjoy
greater privacy at home.
</P>
<P>
Young couples can now visit a wide array of favorite venues
such as new department stores, teahouses, cafes, restaurants and
dance halls.
</P>
<P>
The over 7,000 hectares of city parks also offer a pleasing
environment for young couples.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that many young people have never heard of the Lover's
Promenade. He also noted that the young people of today enjoy a
more colorful life than his generation.
</P>
<P>
While large groups of people continue to enjoy the cool breeze
and beautiful sites along the river levee, the once famous Lover's
Promenade no longer exists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Plans Massive Telecommunications Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing Municipality in
southwest China plans to invest 11.6 billion yuan (1.4 billion
U.S. dollars) over the next three years in developing
telecommunications facilities.
</P>
<P>
The figure will exceed total telecommunications investments
over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, China's newest municipality, lags behind other major
metropolitan areas in terms of telecommunications infrastructure,
especially related facilities in rural areas. The lack of access
to convenient telecommunications has made it inconvenient for
overseas investors to do business in the city.
</P>
<P>
Municipal government statistics show that only 25 percent of
the local villages have access to telephones, with the access rate
some 50 lower than the national average.
</P>
<P>
The local government plans to build the city into
an"information port" in order to improve the investment
environment and promote the development of high technology.
</P>
<P>
Funding over the next three years will mainly be used to build
a main transmission network, exchange platforms, a village
telecommunications network and the telecommunications network in
the Three Gorges area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
