<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges UN Security Council to Resume Comprehensive Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The comprehensive review
of Iraq's compliance with relevant U.N. resolutions is the legal
and moral responsibility of the U.N. Security Council, Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After meeting President of the Security Council Jeremy
Greenstock of Britain, Aziz, who is here for a visit, told
reporters that Iraq had not received sufficient guarantees from
the council that it would conduct an honest review of Iraq's
progress in dismantling its weapons of mass destruction in return
for Iraq's resumption of cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to me that deliberations of the council and the work
on the preparations, the basis, and the framework of the
comprehensive review has not yet reached its final end," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, who has been here for over a week, is trying to work out
a solution to the latest impasse over U.N. arms inspection in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He has held two rounds of talks with U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, which yielded no results. The third round of talks
between Aziz and Annan will take place on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq suspended cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors
in early August, a move the council called totally unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the council's repeated calls for the resumption of
cooperation, Iraq has not changed its stand. Last month, the
Council decided to suspend its regular review of U.N. sanctions
against Iraq until the latter reverses its decision.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the council offered to conduct a comprehensive
review of Iraq's compliance of U.N relevant resolutions once the
nation resumes cooperation with the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
