<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Lashes Out at South Korean-Japanese Fishery Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A leading newspaper in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Wednesday strongly
criticized a South Korean-Japanese fisheries accord, calling it
violation of the sovereignty the Korean nation and a "brutal
trample" on international law.
</P>
<P>
Japan and South Korea in September reached accord on a new
fisheries pact, under which the two countries will establish a
fishing zone around a disputed group of islets in the Sea of
Japan, called Takeshima in Japan and Tokto in South Korea, 35
nautical miles from the shores of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A commentary carried by the Rodong Sinmun newspaper pointed out
that the accord defining Takeshima, or Tokto, as "tentative
waters" where Japan can fish and explore reveals Japan's intention
to incorporate the islets into its territory and establish
administration there.
</P>
<P>
The islets shall never be a bargaining chip, the commentary
emphasized, adding that Japan has no rights to make explorations
in the area. It also urged South Korea to "stop selling out its
territory and resources."
</P>
<P>
Another DPRK official newspaper, Democratic Korea, also carried
an article attacking the South Korean-Japanese accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
