<HEADLINE> Myanmar Signs Project Contracts With Foreign Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar signed about 20 contracts
with foreign companies in the first nine months of this year on a
number of production and exploration projects in the country.
</P>
<P>
These companies are from Australia, Britain, China, Canada,
India, Indonesia, Israel, Japan, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The projects include production of oil, galvanized iron sheet,
machinery, paint, soap powder and cement; building of resort
hotels, container wharves, gems centers; exploration of mineral
resources; culture of pearl and installation of CDMA phones and
micro-wave links.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, foreign investment in Myanmar
in the first six months of this year amounted to 222 million U.S.
dollars in 10 projects, 670.5 million dollars less than that in
the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment from 23 countries and regions totaled 6.8
billion dollars at the end of June this year in 303 projects since
the country opened to foreign investment in late 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
