<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Calls for Political Talks on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
on Tuesday night called for an early resumption of unconditional
talks between the two parties in Kosovo conflicts in order to
achieve "a comprehensive political solution."
</P>
<P>
In an oral statement to the press, Jeremy Greenstock, president
of the 15-member Security Council for October, said that "Council
members insisted on the need for an early resumption of
negotiations, without preconditions, in pursuit of a comprehensive
political settlement of the (Kosovo) crisis."
</P>
<P>
The statement came at the end of the council's consultation on
a report by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who said that the
fighting was intensified in Kosovo after the Security Council
adopted a resolution on September 23 demanding an immediate
ceasefire in Serbia's province of mainly ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"Council members supported the Secretary-General's call for a
thorough investigation, under international supervision or with
international participation, of atrocities committed by all sides
to the conflict," the statement said, adding "They urged the ICTY
(the International Criminal Tribunal for Former Yugoslavia) to
extend its investigations to cover these atrocities."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council members shared Annan's assessment of the
danger of a humanitarian disaster in Kosovo, the statement said,
adding that "they underlined the importance of full and unimpeded
humanitarian access throughout the affected area and the need to
create conditions for the safe return of refugees and displaced
persons to their homes."
</P>
<P>
The Council members asked Annan to consider how he could ensure
that the United Nations Secretariat had "a first-hand capacity" to
assess development on the ground, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council agreed that "there had yet to be full
compliance with all the requirement" of relevant Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, they made clear their determination to see
full and sustained compliance in accordance in accordance with
their responsibilities under the (U.N.) Charter," it added.
</P>
<P>
However, the Security Council noted that "military activity had
appeared to wind down and withdrawals had taken place in recent
days, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The oral statement was made as NATO was preparing for possible
air strikes on Yugoslavia if Belgrade failed to carry out the
resolution requirement.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in his report to the Security Council, said on Monday
that Kosovo had witnessed "appalling atrocities" over the past
weeks, and the Serbian security forces should bear the bulk of the
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua on Tuesday afternoon,
Vladislav Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav Mission to
the United Nations, voiced his dissatisfaction with Annan's
report, saying the report "is one-sided, and inadequate in many
things."
</P>
<P>
Armed conflicts broke out in Kosovo in February this year after
Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's two
million population, have been battling with Serbs for
independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
