<HEADLINE> India Plans to Privatize Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- India's Planning Commission
and the Civil Aviation Ministry have decided to formulate a
master plan for the privatization of airports in the country,
official sources said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They have also agreed on measures to encourage private sector
participation in airport construction and operation, which include
preparation of draft concession agreement to bring about
uniformity in the pacts with different private sector promoters.
</P>
<P>
The Planning Commission plans to spend 34.34 billion rupees
(825.49 million U.S. dollars) on airport development during the
9th five-year plan period (1998-2002). International and domestic
passenger traffic is estimated to grow by about 6 percent and 10
percent respectively during the plan period. Cargo traffic is
expected to rise by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Concrete steps for involving the private sector in development
of airports are necessary as airport construction is highly
capital intensive," officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Authority of India also plans to take up expansion
and modification of existing terminal buildings, construction of
new terminals and complexes at 30 airports in the country at an
estimated cost of some 4.44 billion rupees (97.2 million dollars).
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
