<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Strengthening Architecture of Monetary System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- China's central bank chief
urged world financial leaders at a meeting here to strengthen the
architecture of the international monetary system so as to
effectively prevent and resolve financial crises.
</P>
<P>
"The main cause of the current crisis is that international
cooperation and the evolution of the international financial
system lag far behind economic globalization and the financial
integration process," said Dai Xianglong, Governor of the People's
Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
"The speed of liberalization exceeded the pace of enhancing the
economic management abilities of the crises-hit countries," added
Dai at the first day session of the three-day annual meeting of
the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Dai noted that the faster pace of globalization in the early
1990s has led to a substantial increase in capital flow which has
been beneficial to the world economy.
</P>
<P>
But more and more capital flow and foreign exchange
transactions have become dissociated from production and trade
activities.
</P>
<P>
Speculators with huge sums of capital are able to take large
leveraged positions to control and manipulate markets for profit,
causing volatility, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The international community has not come to a consensus on
effective mechanisms for the monitoring and containment of risks
brought about by volatile capital flow," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that capital account convertibility should be carried
out in an orderly and well sequenced manner. Member countries are
entitled to determine measures to manage capital flow, taking into
consideration of their specific circumstances and stages of
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Drawing on China's experience with foreign exchange management
system reform, he said that "if a country lacks the conditions for
full convertibility, while still in need of foreign capital, it
can keep foreign debt at a reasonable size with well-structured
maturities (debts due at a certain time) through appropriate
foreign exchange management."
</P>
<P>
He called on major industrial countries to take primary
responsibility for maintaining the stability of the international
financial system and the steady growth of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
"They should strengthen the coordination of interest rates and
exchange rate policies to stabilize international financial
markets."
</P>
<P>
He also urged industrial nations to increase their financial
assistance to crises-affected countries, expand their imports from
those countries, and guard against trade protectionism. At the
same time, those huge speculative funds should be well regulated
by the authorities, he added.
</P>
<P>
The governor commended the IMF and the World Bank for their
efforts and contributions in preventing and solving financial
crises in some regions and countries. He hoped the international
financial institutions could play a more effective role in
resolving the current financial crises in Asia, Russia and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the World Bank for increasing the price of its
loans at a time of substantial reductions in capital flowing to
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"This departs from the Bank's long-standing principle of
pricing loans according to the development purpose, thus sending
the wrong signal to international capital markets, harming its
good relations with borrowing members, and eventually hurting its
own reputation," said Dai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
