<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand May Be First Out of Crisis: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Staporn Kavitanon,
secretary-general of the Board of Investment of Thailand (BOI) has
expressed "cautious optimism" that Thailand is well on the way to
being the first nation to emerge from the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Staporn told the British-Thai Business Group Tuesday that
macroeconomic indicators, such as exports, showed a "light at the
end of the tunnel" although gross domestic product (GDP) growth is
still likely to contract by around 8 percent this year, the
Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While the value of Thai exports is likely to decline in U.S.
dollar terms, the volume has risen by 14 percent in the first
seven months this year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of products such as computers, canned seafood, rubber
products and automobiles and components are showing double-digit
growth in dollar terms and traditional exports such as rice and
garments are higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
"Thai exports to the European Union which accounts for some 16
percent of all Thai exports, increased by 12.1 percent during the
first half of 1998 and exports to the United States were also up
sharply," Staporn said.
</P>
<P>
The BOI estimated that exports for this year will exceed 53
billion U.S. dollars which, when combined with declines in
imports, will result in a healthy trade surplus of about 11.5
billion dollars. Staporn said that by the end of the year, the
current account will show a surplus of 15 billion dollars, roughly
14 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed to the healthy flow of foreign direct
investment (FDI). For the first five months of this year, FDI,
according a Bank of Thailand's report, was roughly equivalent to
the 104 billion baht (2.6 billion dollars) received in the whole
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
For the first eight months, the baht traded at a relatively
narrow range of 38-42 to the dollar, despite concerns about the
Japanese yen, the Malaysian ringgit and other regional
currencies. In the past two weeks, the baht has strengthened again
and is now trading under 40 to a dollar, Staporn said.
</P>
<P>
He said the increased stability of the baht permitted the Bank
of Thailand to relax monetary policy allowing interest rates to
fall dramatically.
</P>
<P>
In addition, inflation for September was 7 percent, reducing
the annual forecast to less than 9 percent -- well below the
International Monetary Fund target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
