<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massive Water Project Started in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A massive water project, which
is to cost 48.5 million U.S. dollars, has started in Anuradhapura
city, North Central Province of Sri Lanka, according to the Urban
Development Ministry Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The project, funded by the French government and the Asian
Development Bank, will provide water to the entire city at an
average of 5.5 million gallons a day by the year 2005, ministry
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Anuradhapura, Sri Lanka's ancient capital, is the capital of
North Central Province.
</P>
<P>
The present water system in the city provides 2.2 million
gallons of water per day, which is not enough to meet the needs,
the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
