<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Flood-Hit Industries Get Special Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Bank, the central bank
of the country, has identified about 1,200 flood-affected
industrial units to provide them with special credit for immediate
rehabilitation, The Bangladesh Observer newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank also estimated that the loss of the industrial units
badly-hit by the country's worst-ever flooding will be over 6
billion taka (about 127.7 million U.S. dollars), the report said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has prepared a report on the flood-affected
industrial units after conducting a survey in cooperation with the
specialized and commercial banks and the report is likely to be
submitted to the Finance Ministry soon, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The bank loans for rehabilitating flood-hit industrial units
including garment, small and cottage industries and other
industrial units would be provided on the basis of the Bangladesh
Bank's report.
</P>
<P>
However, the report did not mention the amount of special loans
to be given to the identified flood-affected industrial units.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's estimate of flood damage to the industrial
sector was much lower than that by the Bangladesh Chamber of
Commerce and Industry, which estimated that about 11,000
industrial units had been badly affected by the
over-two-month-long flooding and the loss of the industrial sector
was about 20 billion taka (about 425.5 million dollars), the
report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the central bank in a circular asked the
specialized and commercial banks to give special loans only to the
flood-affected industrial units to be identified by the bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
