<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Sees Financial Crisis Rooted in System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Michel Camdessus, Managing
Director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Tuesday said
the whole financial system, not just individual country, was now
sunk in crisis.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the IMF-World Bank Annual
Meeting, Camdessus said, "We are speaking not just of countries in
crisis, but of a system in crisis, a system not yet sufficiently
adapted to the opportunities and risks of globalization."
</P>
<P>
However, he added that the current situation was not as dire as
in 1928 when the world plunged into recession, and that
"recession on a global scale can be avoided."
</P>
<P>
"If we keep a steady nerve, if all countries pursue stability,
structural adjustment and orderly liberalization of their
economies, this crisis can be overcome. And countries at the heart
of the turmoil can emerge stronger and better prepared for the
challenges of the next decades."
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said existing programs in Asia were working well, and
both exchange rates and interest rates were stabilizing and moving
to more appropriate levels. "Inflation is in check, external
positions have strengthened remarkably as current accounts have
swung from deficit to large surplus," Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
However, Camdessus added that countries need to cooperate "to
repair the major shortcomings in the global system which the
crisis has brought to light."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
