<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Consults U.N. Chief for Better Handling of Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of
Treasury Robert Rubin met with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
here Tuesday evening to discuss how the United Nations can do its
part to help overcome the financial crisis now affecting the world.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a 45-minute caucus in the U.N. building in New
York, Rubin said they focused on the immediate challenges certain
parts of the world will face and prevention of crisis in the
future.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. plays a very important role in nation-building and
institution-building in developing and emerging market countries,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The world body has been trying to deal with long-run problems,
and now it is having an additional burden to bear when the
financial crisis is going to create more poverty and more need for
humanitarian assistance, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"The more serious the crisis comes to certain parts of the
world, the more serious it is going to affect us," Rubin said,
adding that that is why the U.S. sees it so imperative to support
institutions like the U.N., "which are very central to deal with
these problems."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said "it is enormously in the U.S. interests" for his
country to pay its 1.6-billion-U.S.-dollar back dues to the
U.N. and to pay its quota for the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
Annan said they discussed some of the things that the U.N.
tries to do to help governments strengthen their institutions, in
addition to stressing the need for more aid and investment flows
and debt relief for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time a U.S. Secretary of Treasury coming out
of an IMF-World Bank meeting has chosen to consult with a
U.N. Secretary-General, not only on the current crisis, but also
seeking solutions in the long-run, a U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was requested by the U.S. administration, the
official noted.
</P>
<P>
According to Annan, he and Rubin did not discuss specific work
plans, but their discussions would continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
