<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Development Zones Promote Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's development zones have
taken full advantage of the capital's comprehensive investment
environment to record rapid development and emerge as a new focal
point of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Statistics through the end of 1997 show that more than 8,100
enterprises had established operations in the Beijing's New
Technology Experiment Pilot Zone, Economic and Technological
Development Zone and various other industrial zones in the city's
22 districts and counties.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises in the zones recorded a 1997 output value of
25.1 billion yuan (3.02 billion US dollars) and accounted for 14.6
percent of the city's total industrial output value, up
dramatically on the 2.4 percent level for five years ago.
</P>
<P>
High technology operations, which account for some 80 percent
of enterprises in the zones, involve electronic information,
electromechanical, bioengineering, new resource, pharmaceuticals
and building-materials
 sectors.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's development zones have also attracted more than 1,000
foreign enterprises, with contracted foreign funds totalling 3.2
billion US dollars, including foreign direct investment (FDI) of
2.2 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The zones approved 338 foreign-funded enterprises during the
first six months of this year, up 1.5-fold on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Rapid development has been attributed to the improved
investment environment in the Chinese capital and a series of
preferential policies local governments have adopted to attract
foreign funds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
