<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Reiterates not to Re-open MCC Talks With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Panama on Tuesday ruled out
the possibility that it will resume negotiations with the United
States while President Perez Balladares is in power on the setting
up of an anti-drug center in the central American country.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, Panama and the United States have sought to agree
on establishing a Panama-based Multinational Counternarcotics
Center (MCC) in which military personnel from the United States
and other hemispheric countries will take part.
</P>
<P>
But last month, the two countries announced that they failed to
reach an agreement after two years of efforts because the
U.S. insisted that its troops be deployed at the center.
</P>
<P>
Under the Panama Canal treaties, American soliders should leave
by December 31, 1999, when the control of the Panama Canal passes
to the Panamanian government.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge Eduardo Ritter said Tuesday
that before a new government comes into office on September 1,
1999, it will be impossible for Panama to re-open the MCC
negotiations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Ritter made the remarks following an announcement by
U.S. Ambassador to Panama William Hughes, who told local press
that negotiations on establishing the MCC will resume with the
next Panamanian government expected to be elected on May 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Hughes added that Panama is an appropriate country to practice
military operations in the region, and his country is interested
in resuming negotiations over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Ritter said, however, that the U.S. government would be wrong
to re-open the negotiations because the two governments already
decided to end them.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the United States should initiate steps to
dismantle its Howard Air Force base in Panama, which that country
originally intended to turn into the MCC's future headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Builds 15 Power Plants in Eight Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has built 15
hydroelectric power plants in cooperation with the Yunnan
Machinery Equipment Import and Export Corporation (YMEIEC) of
China since 1990, according to Myanmar electric power authorities
sources.
</P>
<P>
The total value of machinery for the plant projects are worth
about 50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the state-run Myanmar Electric Power Enterprise
(MEPE) reached a new 160-million-dollar contract with the YMEIEC
on the implementation of the Paunglaung hydroelectric power
project in Pyinmana, central Mandalay division of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Paunglaung plant is the biggest of its kind and the first
underground factory in Myanmar with an installed capacity of 280
megawatts (mw), accounting for 28 percent of Myanmar's existing
installed capacity.
</P>
<P>
According to the MEPE, added projects for Ye Ywa, Bilin,
Thaukyekhat, Shweli and Kun will be implemented one after another.
</P>
<P>
A recent annual official report on Myanmar's economy revealed
that the installed generating capacity of the MEPE was 1,207 mw in
the 1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March, accounting for 77
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The MEPE generated 4.2 billion kilowatt-hours (kwh) of
electricity in the year, of which 1.6 billion kwh or 39 percent
were produced by hydropower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
