<HEADLINE> Franco-Italian Summit Ends with Wide-Ranging Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Franco-Italian summit closed in
Florence on Tuesday with Italian and French leaders finding common
ground on virtually all subjects they discussed.
</P>
<P>
They made a joint appeal for diplomatic efforts to help end the
Kosovo crisis in Yugoslavia and agreed on the European Union's
institutional reforms and farm policies.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi, France has
asked Italy to reduce interests rates to contribute to the
continent-wide economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini and
his French counterpart Huber Vedrine signed an accord to create a
joint Italian-French university to be based in Turin and Grenoble.
</P>
<P>
However, the summit was overshadowed by an ongoing Italian
government crisis stemmed from differences over the new 1999
budget between Prodi's ruling coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
Even at the press conference after the summit, bilateral issues
were sidelined.
</P>
<P>
"I wouldn't be sincere if I didn't say that there was a cloud
weighing on our discussions," Prodi said, referring to the crisis
which may see his government without a majority in parliament on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
French leaders, on their part, expressed support for the
Italian government.
</P>
<P>
"I want to say that we have the deepest respect for the Italian
government," Chirac said after 90 minutes of talks this morning to
round up the wide-ranging discussions following Monday.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said he believed a solution
would be found to solve the "complex problems" faced by Prodi's
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
