<HEADLINE> Italian Foreign Minister Urges Closer Relations with Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini called for closer relations with Iran during a meeting with
visiting Iranian Parliamentary Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri in
Rome on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dini expressed Rome's support for "the constructive line of
dialogue" launched by Tehran at the United Nation's general
assembly in New York last month.
</P>
<P>
"Once Iran's international relations are fully restored, it
will play a key role in the stability of the Middle East and the
Persian Gulf," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dini said Italy's wish for stronger ties with Iran was
"confirmed by the intensity of the high-level political contacts
between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
The Italian foreign minister visited Iran in March, followed by
Lower House Speaker Luciano Violante in April. Prime Minister
Romano Prodi also made a landmark visit to Tehran in July.
</P>
<P>
Noting that cultural dialogue could play a key role in
bilateral relations, Dini said a series of colloquia with European
and Islamic scholars were being planned by Italy and Iran.
</P>
<P>
At the Lower House in the afternoon, Nouri and Violante signed
a protocol aimed at intensifying strategic relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The protocol called for annual meetings between work groups of
the two houses and encouraged contacts between young deputies and
women in the Italian and Iranian parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Nouri also met with Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro and
Senate Speaker Nicola Mancino on Tuesday. 
</P>
