<HEADLINE> Prodi Confident Government Can Survive Budget Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A confident Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi said on Tuesday that his government has a chance to
steer away from a crisis stemming from differences between
coalition partners over the 1999 draft budget.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a Franco-Italian summit in Florence, Prodi said
his coalition was looking for ways to garner enough votes from its
parliamentary majority to pass the government's 1999 budget.
</P>
<P>
"There's a window still open and we intend to proceed in this
direction," Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
At meetings last weekend, the Communist Refoundation party, the
left ally in the coalition, voted to withhold its vital support
for the budget package in parliament, sparking concerns for the
survival of Prodi's center-left coalition that went into power in
1996.
</P>
<P>
However, the 34 leftist deputies in the Lower House were
sharply divided on the issue. Chairman of the Communist
Refoundation party Armando Cossutta announced his resignation on
Monday to affirm support for Prodi's administration.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said he would brief parliament on the new budget on
Wednesday and asked for a vote of confidence for his government.
</P>
<P>
"If we receive the vote of confidence, we'll continue.
Otherwise we'll hand over the reins," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition led by Prodi's Olive Tree party enjoys a
comfortable majority in the Upper House, but its majority in the
Lower House relies heavily on the backing of the Communist
Refoundation party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
