<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Favors Political Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Romania supports the
international community's stand on the Kosovo crisis, but is still
hopeful that a political solution can be achieved, a statement by
the foreign ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that Yugoslav authorities should comply
with a relevant U.N. Security Council resolution, which demands an
immediate cease-fire, withdrawal of Serb forces, granting
international humanitarian and relief groups free access to
Kosovo, and opening negotiations among conflicting parties,
Romania's Media Fax news agency said.
</P>
<P>
It voiced support for efforts made by the Six-nation Contact
Group for the former Yugoslavia and North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO). It also hoped the international community
would take into consideration opinions and security interests of
other countries in the region and prevent the crisis from
spreading.
</P>
<P>
The statement backs the six-nation contact group, the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), the
European Union, the Council of Europe and the United Nations in
their efforts to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
It suggests the OSCE ensure an effective monitor of the
settlement to the crisis through direct participation by its
permanent missions.
</P>
<P>
The statement also calls on Belgrade to adopt an open manner
and to trust the international community.
</P>
<P>
NATO has threatened to launch an air attack against Yugoslavia
unless Yugoslavia end the conflict with Kosovo ethnic Albanian
separatists and negotiate an autonomy agreement for the southern
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
Russia and many other countries oppose the use of force in
Kosovo. Belgrade has repeatedly claimed that the Kosovo issue is
an internal affair and needs no outside intervention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
