<HEADLINE> Italy, France Call for Diplomatic Efforts in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Threats of military intervention
must be accompanied by diplomatic pressure in urging Yugoslavia to
pull its troops out of Kosovo, Italian and French leaders said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of a two-day French-Italian summit, Italian
Prime Minister Romano Prodi and French President Jacques Chirac
said political efforts to end hostilities should continue as long
as there is hope that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic will
heed them.
</P>
<P>
"The threat of force must be complemented by a diplomatic
political approach," the two leaders said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that both he and Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini are
applying pressure to Milosevic in the hope he will end hostilities
in the ethnic-Albanian province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Dini, who was also present at the summit, indicated however
that Italy will support military intervention if it is necessary
to ensure the arrival of humanitarian aid to the thousands of
people made homeless by the fighting.
</P>
<P>
"This is quite different from just sending in tanks," Dini
said. 
