<HEADLINE> Indonesia Considers Removing Hurdles to Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
considering the removal of regulatory barriers hampering the
country's privatization program, the Jakarta Post Wednesday quoted
a minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
A regulation on the operation of state-owned infrastructure
companies should be revised to speed up the process of privatizing
such companies, State Minister of the Empowerment of State
Enterprises Tanri Abeng said.
</P>
<P>
Existing law stipulates that the firms and the government have
exclusive rights to manage the country's infrastructure sector and
prohibits the selling of shares to private parties.
</P>
<P>
"The government is considering changes in the law and
regulations so the privatization program can be realized," Tanri
told members of the House of Representatives Commission VIII on
state budget on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to privatize 12 state-owned firms during
the 1998-99 fiscal year ending March in order to inject some 1.5
billion U.S. dollars into the state budget in privatization
proceeds.
</P>
<P>
Tanri admitted that the government would not achieve its target
of privatizing 12 state-owned companies in the current fiscal year
because of the regulations and what he called "social-political"
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
Another barrier i the current bearish capital market sentiment
which is causing difficulties in raising a reasonable amount of
cash from the privatization program, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
