<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Reports Rampant Piracy of Computer Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Czech official said that
criminal activities of computer software piracy is becoming
increasingly rampant in the country, with 80 percent of the
software products in the Czech market being results of piracy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of Brno International
Information and Technique Exposition Monday, Interior Minister
Vaclav Grulich said that there were 650 cases of infringement on
intellectual property rights in 1997, but the figure nearly
doubled in the first half of this year to 1,250.
</P>
<P>
Not only individuals, but some commercial companies were
involved in these cases, Grulich said.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the situation, the Czech government has set up
special institutions and organizations to coordinate efforts to
strike at the root of such criminal activities, Grulich said.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that criminal activities of infringement
on intellectual property rights have seriously tarnished the
international image of the Czech Republic and have placed the
country under great pressure.
</P>
<P>
If such a situation is not redressed, the Czech Republic could
listed as an unreliable country, the minister warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
