</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers also announced plans to establish the
Sino-British Forum.
</P>
<P>
-- China has reformed its foreign trade system during the past
two decades and has gained rapid development. Its imports and
exports rose to 325.06 billion US dollars in 1997 from 20.64
billion dollars in 1978, growing at an average annual rate of 15.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- China will create more favorable conditions for Chinese
students studying abroad to encourage them to come back to China,
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing told a visiting group of 36 students
studying abroad yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Li said that rapid economic growth and social development in
China have meant a great need for talented people and students
who have gained a great deal of knowledge in the world. China's
policy of sending students abroad, about 300,000 by now, has
proven fruitful over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
-- About 100 journalists from the Xinhua News Agency, People's
Daily, and other news media were commended yesterday for their
outstanding performance in covering the country's recent fight
against the worst floods in decades.
</P>
<P>
Ding Guangen, head of the Publicity Department of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, told a meeting
at Beijing's Great Hall of the People that the coverage of
the recent floods by Chinese journalists displayed their political
awareness, sense of responsibility, affection for the people, and
excellent work style.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China is concerned by, and opposed to, the United States'
new defence plans which contain some anti-China clauses.
</P>
<P>
"The action wantonly disobeyed the basic norms of the
international law and seriously violated principles set out in the
three Sino-US joint communiques," said Foreign Ministry spokesman
Zhu Bangzao yesterday at a routine press briefing.
</P>
<P>
-- A senior Chinese official hopes Straits Exchange Foundation
(SEF) leader Koo Chen-fu's visit to Beijing will lead to political
talks between Taibei and the central government.
</P>
<P>
Talks can touch on anything under the auspices of the "One
China" stand, said Chen Yunlin, director of the State Council's
Taiwan Affairs Office. 
