<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forex Adjustment Promotes Vietnam's Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The devaluation of the Vietnamese
dong against the U.S. dollar in August has resulted in larger
profit margins for exporters and a lower trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Ngoc Tuan, head of the government Pricing Committee,
said the change brought a 10-percent profit rise for rice export,
7 percent for fisheries export and more than 1,000 Vietnamese dong
profit for each U.S. dollar's worth of coffee exported.
</P>
<P>
The adjustment has had a big impact on imports, but it has also
meant lower import receipts and an improved balance of trade.
</P>
<P>
The government will consider import subsidies for enterprises
which have incurred large losses due to the adjustment, but in
general business people should take this as a personal challenge,
Tuan was quoted Tuesday by the English daily The Saigon Times as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The official also said Vietnam was facing high pressure from
the large difference then between black market and official rates,
which caused the holding of dollars by speculators and
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, Vietnam obtained an export turnover
of 6.93 billion U.S. dollars in the first nine months of this
year, up 4.1 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Import receipts in the nine months reached 8.58 billion
dollars, down 0.3 percent from the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam exports in 1998 are estimated officially at 9 billion
to 9.3 billion dollars, the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in the past nine months was 7.9 percent, mostly
caused by higher prices for rice, which went up by 21 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Trend in Eastern China's Private Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The rapidly growing private
sector in China's Zhejiang Province is changing as investment,
products, and organizations continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more private enterprises have shifted
investment from industry to agriculture and services. In the first
half of this year, the number of individual businesses in
agriculture was up 33.54 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Another trend is for private enterprises to put more funds into
research and development of new products. In the six months to
June, over 1,300 new brands were registered.
</P>
<P>
To improve management and their competitive edge, more private
enterprises are incorporating. During the first half of this year,
some 4,000 corporations were set up in Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
The private enterprises are also actively engaged in the
reorganization of state- and collectively-owned enterprises in the
province. From January to June, they merged with or acquired 460
state- and collectively-owned enterprises. Since 1994, more than
11,200 private enterprises in Zhejiang have left their
collectively-owned status.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang's private economy had an industrial output that
accounted for 38 percent of the provincial total in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
