<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG -- The European Conference on Tuesday condemned the
persistent violence in the Serbian province of Kosovo, calling for
an immediate end to it.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the European Union (EU) member states,
all the 11 applicant countries for EU membership and Switzerland
stressed the importance of the adoption of United Nations Security
Council Resolution 1199.
</P>
<P>
They also urged Belgrade to comply fully and immediately with
the resolution, which calls for an immediate ceasefire, adopted on
September 23. (EU-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Tuesday that the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) was prepared to act in
Kosovo if Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic did not comply
fully with the U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
Clinton gave the warning in a speech to the joint secretariat
meeting of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who spoke to Blair for about 20 minutes on the
telephone about Kosovo Tuesday, said "we all agree that Kosovo is
a powder keg in the Balkans," one that left unchecked could
threaten the stability of other countries in the region.
(US-Clinton-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- New Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov on
Tuesday evening announced that the Russian government has been
formed and started to take emergency measures to stabilize the
situation.
</P>
<P>
In a television address Primakov emphasized that it is a matter
of creating normal living conditions for Russian citizens.
</P>
<P>
The government will perform obligations to pay monetary
allowances to servicemen and to pay current salaries to all
persons on the state payroll, Primakov said, adding current
pensions will be paid in October, and the payments will be further
done every month. (Russia-Primakov-Situation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Tuesday that
concerted global action was needed to resolve the world financial
crisis which was worsening.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that if we act together we can end the present
crisis," Clinton told a joint annual meeting of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Threatening global financial instability and world recession
was centered in the agenda of the meeting, attended by fiance
ministers and central bank governors from member nations at a
Washington hotel.
</P>
<P>
Opening the three-day meeting, Clinton noted that the crisis
has rocked much of Asia and Russia and is now threatening to
damage Brazil and other Latin American nations. Even the U.S.
economy is beginning to feel effects of the crisis with slower job
growth and unstable markets. (US-World Bank-Crisis)  
</P>
</TEXT>
