<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Cancels Malaysia Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie has officially canceled his planned visit to Kuala Lumpur
this month due to heavy state schedules, the Indonesian Observer
Wednesday quoted a minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The president's planned visit to Kuala Lumpur would have meant
a consultation with Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and would be
his first overseas tour since he assumed the post in May, Foreign
Minister Ali Alatas said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that the president is also uncertain whether
or not to attend the coming Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation
Forum (APEC) meeting in Malaysia on November 17-18.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Thai newspaper the Nation on Sunday,
Habibie said he was "very concerned" about the reported treatment
of dismissed Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim and
would have to consult the House of Representatives on whether to
attend the APEC summit in Kuala Lumpur. 
