<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Resumes Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Two weeks after being officially
closed, Philippine Airlines (PAL) Wednesday took to the blue sky
again with the operation of 19 domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
The first flight out of Manila took off at 4:40 a.m. for
Zamboanga, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The national flag carrier first restored flights to 14 domestic
destinations, mostly the major cities in the Philippines. The PAL
management said the resumption of international service will also
be resumed on October 15.
</P>
<P>
PAL announced its re-opening on October 2 following the
favorable outcome of a two-day referendum among PAL ground
employees belonging to the PAL Employees Association and the PAL
management.
</P>
<P>
In the referendum, 61 percent of the employees said "yes" to an
agreement brokered by President Joseph Estrada between the
management and the employees.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the management will give to the employees
20 percent of the PAL ownership and three seats in the 12-seat
board of directors in exchange for the suspension of the labor's
collective bargaining agreement for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
PAL closed shop on September 23 due to heavy financial losses
and the breakdown of talks between the management and the PAL
Employees Association.
</P>
<P>
PAL's closure dealt a heavy blow to the country's air traffic
and economy. President Estrada worked hard to save the oldest
airlines in Asia and finally persuaded the two sides to reach the
agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
