<HEADLINE> Shearer to Stay in Newscastle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Newcastle United striker Alan
Shearer has reaffirmed his desire to stay at the club after new
reports that he could quit the success-starved club.
</P>
<P>
The Magpies have failed to win a trophy since Shearer moved to
St James' Park for 15 million in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Question marks about his future on Tyneside were raised when
Ruud Gullit took charge in August but seven goals in four games
put an end to those doubts.
</P>
<P>
However, following Newcastle's 3-0 defeat at Arsenal on
Sunday, Shearer reiterated his wish to be part of winning set-up.
That was interpreted as a threat to quit but he insists he is
prepared to give Gullit a chance to turn things around.
</P>
<P>
Shearer said: "I have already pledged my support, commitment
and future to Newcastle United and despite misleading headlines
this morning, this remains the case."
</P>
<P>
Shearer has been repeatedly linked with a move to the
continent both before and after joining the Magpies from
Blackburn, with Barcelona one of the clubs said to be interested
in him.
</P>
<P>
Aston Villa manager John Gregory also came out this season and
said he wanted to sign Shearer but his bid was rejected by both
club and player. 
</P>
</TEXT>
