<HEADLINE> BSkyB Hold Purse Strings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Manchester United will have to
get permission from BSkyB if they want to sign any new players
for more than one million pounds (about 1.68 million U.S.
dollars) until a final decision is made on the satellite TV
company's takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
BSkyB have made a 623.4 million pounds offer for the Old
Trafford club and shareholders have until October 26 to give
their reply.
</P>
<P>
But the deadline could be extended if the Office of Fair
Trading has not reached a conclusion on whether the proposed deal
contravenes government regulations by that date.
</P>
<P>
United would normally not be allowed to conduct any transfer
deals, but Sky have agreed to waive their veto up to the one
million mark.
</P>
<P>
A company spokeswoman insisted they would make no attempt to
influence United in the transfer market.
</P>
<P>
She said: "Clearly BSkyB has no interest in preventing the
successful running of Manchester United either during the offer
period or once the acquisition is completed. We have no intention
of doing so."
</P>
<P>
United chairman Sir Roland Smith promised on Monday that
manager Alex Ferguson would remain in complete control of team
affairs and the board would continue to oversee the day-to-day
running of the club. 
</P>
</TEXT>
