<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Poor People Reduces in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- China's poverty-stricken
population fell from 80 million at the beginning of the 90s to 50
million at the end of 1997, according to China's Deputy Permanent
Representative to the United Nations Shen Guofang.
</P>
<P>
However, the unprecedented summer floods made its
poverty-relief task more formidable, he told the U.N. General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly was in session to deal with the implementation of
the Outcome of the World Summit for Social Development held in
Copenhagen in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The flooding has affected 21.2 million ha of land and 223
million people, with a direct economic loss of over 20 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shen said the Chinese Government has always made the
elimination of poverty an important part of its program for
national economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
It strives to ensure resources input into the poverty
eradication program by earmarking funds and preferential loans to
poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly decided in 1992 to convene a special
session in 2000 to review the follow-up action since the
Copenhagen summit. preparations for the session have already
begun.
</P>
<P>
Shen stressed that as countries differ in their economic basis,
political systems and cultural traditions, they should implement
effective social development strategies and plans in line with
their national conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Jones Industrial Average Finishes with Small Gain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Blue chip stocks closed with a
small gain, but most other stocks at Wall Street turned lower
Tuesday after a morning rally as investors remained skeptical
about the results of the multinational talks in Washington aimed
at healing the ailing world economy.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average finished at 7,753, 27 points
higher than that on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators finished lower despite a morning rally
fueled by Monday's late rebound, big gains on foreign markets and
other positive signs both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones, which lost 58 points on Monday after rallying
back from a 232-point slide fueled by fears about the negative
results of the Washington meetings, is about 1,600 points below
its historic peak of 9,337.97 on July 17.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has been calling for concerted
and bold actions by the world's leading industrial nations to
contain the growing financial crisis in Asia and Russia. But his
calls has not yet got positive response from U.S. partners in
the Group 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia not Satisfied With Annan's Kosovo Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Yugoslav
diplomat on Tuesday voiced his dissatisfaction with a Monday
report by U.N. Secretary-General who said that the Serb security
forces should bear the bulk of responsibility of what has been
reported as atrocities in Kosovo, Serbia's province of mainly
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"We are not satisfied with the report at all, because it is one
sided and inadequate in many things," said Vladislav Jovanovic,
charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua here, Jovanovic said, "By
naming Yugoslavia and Serbia the primarily responsible for the
situation in Kosovo, the report turned things upside down."
</P>
<P>
In fact, the primarily responsible side is the side which has
started terrorism in Kosovo, he said, referring to the action by
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo to seek independence by force.
</P>
<P>
In his report which suggested Yugoslav forces had made only a
limited withdrawal, Annan blamed Serbian security forces for most
atrocities against Kosovo Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
"The accusations are unfounded, and the allegation is totally
misplaced and misguided," he said.
</P>
<P>
He argued that the Yugoslav Government has the right to fight
against terrorism and separatism and to maintain security and
uphold the nation's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement as NATO is preparing a possible air
strike on Yugoslavia if Belgrade fails to carry out the September
23 Security Council resolution, which called for an immediate
ceasefire in Kosovo and the beginning of political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"The reality is that there are some positive development on the
ground -- there is no fighting and no humanitarian catastrophe in
Kosovo, and the government has provided refugees with everything
including materials to repair their houses, tools and clothes, and
the government has guaranteed their security," he said, "Life in
Kosovo is nearly normal."
</P>
<P>
However, the ethnic Albanian secessionists and terrorists
advised the refugees and displaced people to stay in the woods
instead of returning home, so that Western media can have some
photos and file some news stories in order to "create an image of
humanitarian catastrophe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Such a move by the ethnic Albanian terrorists, and Western
media has "made the situation much more complicated" in Kosovo, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Government of Serbia, a main republic of Yugoslavia, on
Monday denounced Western media for having "manipulated their own
public using numerous fabrications and lies about the situation in
Kosovo" in order to help NATO with legal basis for the use of
force against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav foreign minister, during his participation at the
just-concluded general debate of the 53rd General Assembly
session, extended an invitation to Annan to pay a visit to Kosovo
himself so that the U.N. chief "can get the first-hand information
on what is going on in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Annan, through his spokesman Fred Eckhard, said he was kept
well-informed by such groups as the six-nation Contact Group, the
U.N. High Commission for Refugees, and his special representative
for Children and Armed Conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"Even his report was issue, Mr. Annan still has the need to
visit Kosovo himself," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jovanovic, former foreign minister of Yugoslavia,
voiced his appreciation of China's efforts to uphold justice and
the principle of the U.N. Charter at the international community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA Announce Football Shake-up (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- UEFA will introduce an expanded
32-team European Champions' League from next season, an increase
of eight teams, Lennart Johansson, president of European soccer's
governing body, said in Lisbon on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Johansson also confirmed that the European Cup Winners' Cup,
inaugurated in the 1960/61 season, was to be discontinued after
this season to be merged with an enlarged UEFA Cup.
</P>
<P>
"UEFA will invite all our member clubs to participate but we
will not force anyone to be part of our family," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
"A private company wanted to take over the best part of our
club competitions and have appealed to the European Commission to
help them do so but the European Commission can take what
decision it likes.
</P>
<P>
"I am not prepared to sit back and let this happen. We are
perfectly entitled to organize our own competitions and will do
so -- and I am confident our member clubs feel the same way and
will be part of them."
</P>
<P>
In all nearly 200 European clubs would be involved in UEFA's
competitions. Even though the Cup Winners' Cup is being
discontinued after 38 seasons to be merged into an expanded UEFA
Cup, more clubs than ever would have the chance to play in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The plans for the Champions' League have been at the center of
UEFA's deliberations.
</P>
<P>
All of Europe's 48 national champions, plus runners-up,
third-placed teams and fourth-placed teams from the top nations
will be eligible to take part in the competition -- a total of 71
teams.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen teams, plus the previous season's champions, will
automatically qualify for the first-round group stage -- and they
will be joined by 16 survivors from three qualifying rounds
played in July and August.
</P>
<P>
Those 32 teams will then be placed in eight groups of four
teams with the top two in each group advancing to a second round
of 16 -- comprising four groups of four.
</P>
<P>
The top two teams in those groups will advance to the
two-legged quarter-final knockout stage with the winners
advancing through to the final.
</P>
<P>
The two teams who reach the final would have played 17 matches
-- but if they had won through from the three qualifying rounds
they could have played 23 matches in the competition all season.
</P>
<P>
As now, the losers in the qualifying rounds will switch to the
UEFA Cup for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
UEFA have been galvanized into action by the Milan-based
sports marketing group Media Partners, who are planning to
organize a 36-team European Super League with prize money of 1.2
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
They are also proposing a new knock-out competition called the
Pro Cup comprising 96 teams -- and have made a formal complaint
to the European Commission, saying UEFA are abusing their
dominant position by preventing independent bodies organizing and
marketing football competitions in Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA Announce Football Shake-up (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johansson hit back on Tuesday. "UEFA will go on to set the
pace in European football and defend the principles of solidarity
and central marketing.
</P>
<P>
"There will be more money available for the clubs in our
competition and under our new proposals nobody will lose anything.
</P>
<P>
"We are in a position to give more to the top associations and
to open the door wider to the smaller associations."
</P>
<P>
Although the UEFA prize money on offer was not confirmed on
Tuesday it is believed to be between 600-800 million Swiss francs
(446-595 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
While that sum is lower than the prize money being offered by
Media Partners, it is considerably more than UEFA were offering
before talk of a breakaway Super League began last summer.
</P>
<P>
Guido Tognoni, the project manager of UEFA's European Club
Football 2000 Task Force which has worked out the formats for the
new competitions, said: "UEFA is like a cast-iron banker's
guarantee. I am sure the clubs will now be more confident about
UEFA's proposals.
</P>
<P>
"Who can be sure of what money will really be put on the table
by anybody else?"
</P>
<P>
UEFA executive committee member Dr. Joseph Mifsud of Malta
added: "We are very confident about the future of European
football under UEFA. We know why this has come about but the
expansion of the Champions' League was always inevitable and
would probably have happened in a year, maybe two in any case.
</P>
<P>
"As it is, perhaps this is not just about money but also about
integrity based on sporting criteria and not on an elitist idea p
ut about by others."
</P>
<P>
The details of the two re-styled competitions will be
fine-tuned over the next two months and are expected to be
ratified by the next UEFA committee meeting in Tel Aviv in
December.
</P>
<P>
UEFA's decision comes after pressure from Europe's leading
teams over the last two months to overhaul their club
competitions.
</P>
<P>
Several sides, including English Premiership giants Manchester
United, Arsenal and Liverpool, had been in discussions with Media
Partners International over forming a European Super League.
</P>
<P>
However, the clubs came under pressure from FIFA, who
threatened to suspend any team who signed up for the Super League.
</P>
<P>
Media Partners president Rodolfo Hecht, who on Friday filed a
complaint for restrictive practices against UEFA with the
European Union, said that UEFA's executive committee, who are
meeting this week in Lisbon, should revise their decision and
accept his company's ideas on reforming the major European
competitions.
</P>
<P>
"All the major European clubs have already recognized that the
European Football League (EFL) offers them massively revamped
competitions and matches of the highest level," the Italian said.
</P>
<P>
Media Partners proposals are to replace the three official cup
competitions run by UEFA with a midweek Super League of 36 teams
and a Pro Cup with 96 clubs from 51 countries, starting in
2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
However, Sepp Blatter, President of world football's governing
body FIFA, warned on September 25 that any clubs who sign up for
the proposed privately-backed Super League will be suspended.
</P>
<P>
Blatter, speaking after a FIFA Executive meeting, stressed
that the world governing body would take a tough line against any
attempt to break up the "family of football".
</P>
<P>
FIFA would ask the club's national football federation to
suspend the team, thereby preventing them from playing in their
national league or any continental cup competition.
</P>
<P>
The tough line was taken in a resolution by FIFA's executive
after a two-day meeting, saying that its principles of solidarity
"are under direct attack by commercial companies with the
agreement of certain prestigious clubs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981007.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF, World Bank to Resume Talks on New Loan with Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) decided to give a last chance to
Romania, and start talks on possible new loans at the end of this
month, the Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile said Tuesday when
returning from Washington.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian Prime Minister was on a visit to Washington to
attend the annual meeting of IMF and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Radu Vasile said the two international financial bodies made
the decision after talks with the Romanian delegation. He added
that he had asked the two financial bodies to support Romania in
the following 3-6 months so the world financial crisis' effects be
by then diminished.
</P>
<P>
According to the Prime Minister, talks with the World Bank for
the ASAL (Agriculture Sector Adjustment Loan) program would
start at end-October. Depending on results of negotiations,
Romania would receive as many as 150 million U.S. dollars. The
World Bank would also grant financial support in the field of
social protection to start the implementation of two programs: the
Fund for social protection and that for the closing of certain
mines.
</P>
<P>
A far as the IMF was concerned, Poul Thomsen, head of the new
team of IMF negotiators would come to Bucharest at the end of
October to start talks for the conclusion of a new stand-by loan
arrangement, said Radu Vasil.
</P>
<P>
Both IMF and the World Bank representatives noticed the slow
pace of privatization and restructuring of the banking sector,
said Radu Vasile, adding that the IMF representatives expressed
dissatisfaction that in over 8 years, six stand-by accords settled
with Romania's governments were locked in and, as a result, this
would be "the last effort to granting trust to the Romanian
government". And for this, said the Prime Minister, some new
"political crisis elements or instability" would be but in
Romania's disadvantage, and "Romania will become a country in
stoppage of payments," Radu Vasile ended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
