<HEADLINE> Liberia Asks U.S. Ship to Leave Its Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian government Tuesday
urged the U.S. to remove "without precondition" a military vessel
it has deployed within the West African country's territorial
waters, a report from Monrovia said.
</P>
<P>
"Liberia will welcome the withdrawal without any precondition
in the spirit of diplomatic interaction for the mutual benefit of
both countries," it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The arrival and deployment of the U.S. military vessel in
Liberian territorial waters is in violation of Liberia's
territory integrity and sovereignty," added the statement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ship with 30 marines on board was deployed after the
18-19 September clashes between supporters of former faction
leader Roosevelt Johnson and government forces, in case it needs
to evacuate its citizens from Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Johnson fled into the U.S. embassy to take refugee and was
later flown out of Liberia by a helicopter. He is now reportedly
under protective custody in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
While Johnson was negotiating with embassy officials for
admission, Liberian security forces reportedly opened fire at
people inside the embassy, killing two close aides of Johnson and
injuring two embassy staff.
</P>
<P>
The incident has caused tension between the Liberian and U.S.
governments. For this Washington has closed its embassy and
evacuated some of its staff members and their families.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. also demanded a thorough investigation of the
shooting incident and apology from the Liberian government.
</P>
</TEXT>
