<HEADLINE> Women to Be Honored for Work Against Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Five women from the
Dominican Republic, France, India, Jordan and Uganda will be
honored by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) for their
efforts to overcome poverty, the UNDP announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They are Sonia Beltre, Nicole Rouvet, Fatima Bee, Miyasser
Al-Saadi and Edith Wakumire respectively. They will receive the
UNDP award at an event on October 16 sponsored by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to reinforce the U.N. fight for the
rights of the world's poorest citizens.
</P>
<P>
The event to observe the International Day for the Eradication
of Poverty (October 17) will see UNDP Administrator James Gustave
Speth launch a global"race against poverty."
</P>
<P>
The UNDP is scheduled to release a report examining national
and global progress made against poverty since the World Summit
for Social Development in 1995.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 1.3 billion people live in extreme poverty and
lack basic health, sanitation and education services, surviving on
less than 1 U.S. dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP has made poverty eradication its chief goal in its 174
program countries and territories. 
</P>
