<HEADLINE> Mubarak: Egypt Offers Concept to Defuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said Tuesday he offered Turkish President Suleyman Demirel all
possible means to settle the emerging dispute with Syria during
his flash visit to Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Strained ties between Mideast neighbors Syria and Turkey have
deteriorated in recent weeks with Syria bridling at Turkey's
growing military links with Israel and Turkey threatening Damascus
for allegedly aiding Kurdish rebels fighting for autonomy in
southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made a several-hour visit to Turkey and Syria Tuesday
in his bid to contain the escalating tensions between the Mideast
neighbors from developing into armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In statements to the journalists aboard the same plane that
took him back from Ankara to Damascus, Mubarak said he had offered
a set of proposals for the Turkish side to study.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt has offered both Syria and Turkey a purely Egyptian
concept for the settlement of the dispute in order to start a
direct dialog that would lead up to an immediate solution," noted
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
"The ideas propose both sides to meet to discuss the problem
which emanates mainly from the destructive activities of the
Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) in Turkey," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he has the impression after his four-hour closed-door
meeting with Demirel that the PKK issue has caught extreme concern
of the Turkish public opinion.
</P>
<P>
"But I have assured Demirel that it is extremely difficult to
our region to bear any more military showdowns especially that the
current atmosphere is electrified and brim with doubts," said
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
"I said that the only solution now is to give way for
negotiations and dialog.
</P>
<P>
"I will be in contact with presidents Demirel and Assad after
this shuttle tour when both will have started studying our ideas
which aim to open up the doors of dialog and negotiations," he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Middle East News Agency, Egypt will brief
Turkey on the outcome of the meeting Mubarak had with Syrian
President Hafez al Assad in which Mubarak spoke of the results of
his talks with the Turkish leader.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing efforts aim at arranging a meeting between the
foreign ministers of Turkey and Syria and opening the road
for the resumption of their joint committee meetings in a bid to
contain the mounting tension between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Although Egyptian officials refused to disclose details of
Mubarak's trip, Turkish newspapers said Mubarak will be carrying
to Ankara a plan on gradual reconciliation between Turkey and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
This plan might lead to holding a series of Turkish-Syrian
ministerial meetings, probably to be followed by a quadrilateral
summit that would include the leaders of Egypt and Saudi Arabia,
according to the Turkish press Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's trip to Ankara came between the two rounds of talks
between Mubarak and Syrian President Hafez al-Assad in Damascus
Sunday and late Tuesday. Mubarak has called on both sides to
restrain from any provocative actions.
</P>
<P>
Both sides appear to have pulled back from the brink in recent
days with separate announcements they sought diplomat means to
resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said on Saturday that
Turkey plans a military exercise along the Syrian border after the
end of current NATO exercises in the area.
</P>
<P>
It also announced plans for fresh naval maneuvers in the
eastern Mediterranean and joint air exercises, which Syria says
directed against itself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
