<HEADLINE> Khatami: Afghan Issue Cannot be Solved Through </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami reiterated here on Tuesday that the Afghan crisis could
not be solved through military means.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with visiting U.N. envoy Lakhdar Brahimi,
Khatami said that real peace could be restored in Afghanistan
only when the Afghan people have the capability to decide their
own fate.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that those resorting to force should be pressured
to respect the international norms and laws, the official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the Taliban occupied the whole Afghanistan and drove
the other groups out of the scene, tranquillity would not return
to Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president underlined the needs for international
organizations, particularly the U.N. and the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC), as well as neighboring countries to
cooperate to restore peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
On Iran's military deployment along the border with
Afghanistan, Khatami said that Iran would not accept insecurity
on its borders even though "we believe that war is not the first
choice to solve issue."
</P>
<P>
Iran has deployed more than 200,000 troops along its border
with Afghanistan after eight Iranian diplomats and a reporter were
killed by the Taliban in August.
</P>
<P>
Any country would defend its independence and security on its
borders, Khatami said, adding that the Taliban should respect
international laws and norms.
</P>
<P>
He called on U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to put pressures
on the Taliban to return the remaining bodies of Iranian
diplomats killed in Afghanistan, release other Iranians captured
by the Taliban and punish those responsible for the killing of
Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi, who arrived here on Sunday to defuse the tensions
between Iran and Taliban, underlined the need for international
organizations to join hands to solve the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
Anyone will not oppose, but support Iran's demand for the
release of Iranian citizens under Taliban's captivity, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
