<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2115 GMT, October 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright started her two-day shuttle diplomacy in the Middle East
Tuesday morning by holding talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived in Israel Monday night, is on a mission
to bring the Israelis and the Palestinians closer to an agreement
over the second Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank, thus paying
the way for a four-day Middle East summit in Washington in
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
This was the first trip of the secretary of state to the region
in over a year. She is accompanied by U.S. Middle East envoy
Dennis Ross and Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk.
(Albright-Israel-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- On the 25th anniversary of the 1973 October War
against Israel Tuesday, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak termed
the Egyptian victory in the war as a gateway to peace.
</P>
<P>
"The October War was, undoubtedly, a bright mark in Egypt's
military history, it was not a war for the sake of war, but a war
to pave the path for peace," Mubarak said in an interview with
Good Morning Egypt television Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian army launched a surprise attack on October 6, 1973 and
crossed the Suez Canal into the Israeli-occupied Sinai
peninsular. Israel captured the peninsular in the 1967 Middle East
War. (Egypt-October War-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel Tuesday accused
Syria of supporting the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK)
during his talks with visiting Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the presidential press center said that
Demirel explained the attitude of Syria which supports PKK to
Mubarak during their talks.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak arrived here Tuesday to find ways to defuse the
escalating crisis between Ankara and Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Demirel told Mubarak that Syria must stop supporting the PKK,
and the necessary concrete steps must be taken in the settlement
to the PKK issue, said the statement. (Turkey-Egypt-Syria)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERICO, WEST BANK -- Both Israel and the Palestinians have to
make "hard choices" in order to put the peace process back on
track quickly, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference with Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat after almost two hours of talks, Albright
said the time "is not on our sides" and therefore Israel and the
Palestinians have to move forwards the peace negotiations
quickly.
</P>
<P>
She declined to go into details about her meeting with Arafat
and the previous one held Tuesday morning with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, but said these meetings were
"useful."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state is on a mission trying to bring the
two sides closer to an agreement over the Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank, which would pave the way for a four-day Middle East
summit in Washington in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived in Israel Monday night, held more than
two hours of inconclusive talks Tuesday morning with Netanyahu,
but there was no report of progress. She will meet Netanyahu
again in the evening. (Albright-Arafat-Talks)


06/10/98 21:20 GMT

NNNN
05:16 05:17 g # PAB
</P>
